ritish Academy Games Award for Performer|Performer in a Leading Role]] <small>(Courtney Hope)</small>\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[British Academy Games Award for Performer|Performer in a Supporting Role]] <small>(Martti Suosalo)</small>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[British Academy Games Award for Technical Achievement|Technical Achievement]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 18th Annual G.A.N.G. Awards\n| Best Dialogue\n| {{Pending}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Wilson |first=Kelly |date=13 February 2020 |url=https://www.thehypemagazine.com/2020/02/game-audio-network-guild-announces-18th-annual-g-a-n-g-award-nominees/ |title=Game Audio Network Guild Announces 18th Annual G.A.N.G. Award Nominees |publisher=The Hype Magazine |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Original Instrumental\n| {{Pending}}\n|-\n| Best Original Soundtrack Album\n| {{Pending}}\n|-\n| Best Audio Mix\n| {{Pending}}\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.controlgame.com/}}'''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/top-10-naval-battle-games-for-pc-2020.html top 1o best games][https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/ Games Sotre]'''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/ free Games'''online Acrade Games'''  ''Puzzel Games''   '''Best Gmaing free Download Websites''']\n\n{{Remedy Entertainment}}\n\n[[Category:2019 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Third-person shooters]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One X enhanced games]]\n[[Category:505 Games]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Finland]]\n[[Category:Video games set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Remedy Entertainment games]]\n[[Category:Video games about the paranormal]]\n[[Category:Video games about psychic powers]]\n[[Category:Science fiction video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional government investigations of the paranormal]]\n[[Category:Weird fiction video games]]\n[[Category:Video games that support DirectX 12]]\n[[Category:Interactive Achievement Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|2019 action-adventure video game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Control\n| image = D1IOd0BWsAAiX5T.jpg\n| developer = [[Remedy Entertainment]]\n| publisher = [[505 Games]]\n| director = Mikael Kasurinen\n| producer = Juha Vainio\n| designer = Paul Ehreth\n| programmer = Sean Donnelly\n| artist = Janne Pulkkinen\n| writer = {{Unbulleted list|[[Sam Lake]]|Josh Stubbs}}\n| composer = {{Unbulleted list|Petri Alanko|[[Martin Stig Andersen]]}}\n| engine = <!-- Blank because of Wikidata -->\n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]}}\n| released = 27 August 2019\n| genre = [[Third-person shooter]], [[action-adventure]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Control''''' is an [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[video game]] developed by [[Remedy Entertainment]] and published by [[505 Games]]. The game revolves around the Federal Bureau of Control (FBC), a secret U.S. government agency tasked with containing and studying phenomena that violate the laws of reality. As Jesse Faden (Courtney Hope), the Bureau's new Director, players explore the Oldest House \u2013 the FBC's paranormal headquarters \u2013 and utilize powerful abilities in order to defeat a deadly enemy known as the Hiss, which has invaded and corrupted reality. ''Control'' was released on 27 August 2019 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox One]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jeff |first1=Cork |title=Control Is Coming Out This August |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/03/21/control-is-coming-out-this-august |website=Game Informer |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nUpon release, ''Control'' was met with positive reviews from critics and consumers alike, with some gaming publications naming it one of the top 10 games of 2019. ''Control'' was followed by a downloadable expansion, ''The Foundation'', which was released on March 26, 2020. A second expansion, ''AWE'', is scheduled for release in mid-2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://controlgame.com/control-community-blog-whats-new/|title=Control Community Blog \u2013 What\u2019s Next? |publisher=[[Remedy Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Control'' is played from a [[third-person perspective]], and is built using Remedy's proprietary Northlight Engine, which was first used on the company's previous title ''[[Quantum Break]]''. As Jesse Faden, players wield the Service Weapon, a supernatural firearm that can be adapted into a variety of different forms with different combat applications.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vader |first1=Leo |title=Remedy's Control Only Has One Gun. Here's Why It's Awesome |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/video-feature/2019/03/13/remedys-control-only-has-one-gun-heres-why-its-awesome |website=Game Informer |accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref> In addition to the Service Weapon, Jesse possesses a variety of supernatural abilities including telekinesis, levitation, quick dash and the ability to seize certain enemies. The Service Weapon has limited ammunition which reloads after a certain interval and Jesse's abilities expend Jesse's energy, necessitating a balance in their usage. The Service Weapon can be upgraded throughout the game via a skill tree; in order to gain new powers.The Service Weapon is a gun that can transform into 5 different forms: Grip, Spin, Shatter, Pierce, Charge. players must locate various Objects of Power - ordinary items acted upon by supernatural forces - hidden throughout the Oldest House. Due to the versatility of the game's loadouts, ''Control''{{'}}s combat system can be customized and balanced to each player's personal preferences.<ref name=\"gameinformer.com\">{{cite web |last1=Shea |first1=Brian |title=A Look At Every Supernatural Ability In Remedy's Control |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/03/08/a-look-at-every-supernatural-ability-in-remedys-control |website=Game Informer}}</ref> Health in ''Control'' does not recharge automatically, and must be picked up from fallen enemies.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=@bacon_sandwich |number=1106796905244344321 |date=15 March 2019 |title=I think you\u2019ll be happy to learn in Control, player health does not regenerate automatically. It is dropped from enemies as you damage them, and you have decide when to collect it }}</ref>\n\n''Control'' is set within the Oldest House, a featureless [[Brutalist architecture|Brutalist]] skyscraper in [[New York City]], which is referred to in-game as a \"Place of Power\". The Oldest House's interior is far larger than its exterior, an enormous, constantly shifting supernatural realm that defies the laws of [[spacetime]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shea |first1=Brian |title=Uncovering The Mysteries Of Control's The Oldest House |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/03/15/uncovering-the-mysteries-of-controls-the-oldest-house |website=Game Informer |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref> ''Control'' is built in the [[Metroidvania]] format, with a large world map that can be explored at a nonlinear pace, unlike Remedy's previous titles, which were primarily linear. As the player unlocks new abilities and clearance throughout the game, new areas of the Oldest House can be explored, opening various side-quests. Certain areas known as Control Points can be used to fast travel throughout the building after they have been cleared of enemies. A new A.I. system known as the Encounter Director controls interactions with enemies based on the player's level and location in the Oldest House.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Favis |first1=Elise |title=How Control's Gameplay Differs From Past Remedy Games |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/03/11/how-controls-gameplay-differs-from-past-remedy-games |website=Game Informer |accessdate=11 March 2019}}</ref> Enemies in ''Control'' are predominantly human agents of the FBC possessed by the Hiss, an otherworldly force. They range from standard humans carrying firearms to heavily mutated variations which possess a variety of superpowers. Some of Jesse's abilities allow her to seize control of enemies' minds temporarily, turning them into her allies, and allowing their abilities to be used for the player's benefit.<ref name=\"gameinformer.com\"/>\n\n==Synopsis==\n===Setting===\n''Control'' revolves around a clandestine U.S. government agency known as the Federal Bureau of Control (FBC), which is responsible for the investigation of \"paranatural\" phenomena which defy the known laws of reality. These phenomena manifest in the form of Altered World Events (AWEs), intrusions upon perceived reality shaped by the human [[collective unconscious]]. These AWEs affect [[Jungian archetypes|archetypal]] objects and give them unique properties; referred to as Altered Items by the Bureau, they are contained within their headquarters at the Oldest House, an enormous [[Brutalist architecture|Brutalist]] skyscraper in [[New York City]]. AWEs produce Objects of Power, which are unique in that they grant certain individuals (referred to as \"parautilitarians\") paranatural abilities. Objects of Power are connected to the Astral Plane, an alternate dimension housing the Board, a pyramid-shaped entity which ordains the Bureau's leadership through a ritual connected to the Service Weapon, an Object of Power. Whomever the Board chooses to wield the Service Weapon is considered by default to be the Director of the FBC.<ref name=\"vice mythos\">{{cite web | url = https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/j5ypj3/control-the-board-pyramid | title = The Mysterious \"Board\" in 'Control' Is One of the Game's Best, Most Unsettling Ideas | first = Cameron | last = Kunzelman | date = 4 September 2019 | accessdate = 4 September 2019 | work = [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] }}</ref> The Oldest House itself is referred to as a Place of Power by the FBC; on the interior, it is an infinite, constantly shifting paranatural space connected to various [[Parallel universes in fiction|alternate dimensions]] through rooms known as Thresholds.\n\nThe protagonist of ''Control'' is Jesse Faden, who arrives at the Oldest House seeking the whereabouts of her younger brother, Dylan. Seventeen years prior to the game's events, Jesse and Dylan were involved in an AWE in their hometown of Ordinary, [[Wisconsin]] involving a [[slide projector]] Object of Power capable of opening portals to other dimensions. After the Slide Projector's paranatural properties resulted in the disappearance of Ordinary's adult population, the FBC apprehended Dylan and the Slide Projector while Jesse fled, burning all but one of the slides. Jesse arrives at the Oldest House through the guidance of Polaris, a paranatural entity which rescued her and Dylan during the Ordinary AWE.\n\nThroughout the game, Jesse encounters various allies in the FBC, including research specialist Emily Pope, security chief Simon Arish, Head of Operations Helen Marshall, and Ahti, a mysterious Finnish janitor. She also learns of the FBC's former Director, Zachariah Trench, and finds various informative videos created by Dr. Casper Darling, the Bureau's missing Head of Research.\n\n===Plot===\nJesse Faden arrives at the Oldest House under the telepathic guidance of Polaris, finding the building seemingly devoid of people. She bumps into a Finnish janitor, Ahti, who directs her to an elevator for her \"interview.\" Through the elevator, Jesse discovers that the Federal Bureau of Control's Director, Zachariah Trench, has seemingly committed suicide with his own sidearm. Picking it up, Jesse learns that it is an Object of Power known as the Service Weapon, and is transported to the Astral Plane, where she completes a ritual and is selected as the new Director by the Board. Jesse emerges from Trench's office and finds that the Oldest House has been invaded by a hostile force she dubs \"the Hiss,\" which has possessed most of the Bureau's agents and corrupted the building's shifting topography. Jesse uses an Object of Power known as the Hotline to listen to the lingering presence of Trench, who relays that his former management team knows the secrets of the Bureau, and Jesse hopes they may be able to tell her the whereabouts of her brother, Dylan, who was kidnapped by the FBC years prior.\n\nJesse aids Emily Pope and the other remaining agents of the FBC, who have survived by donning Hedron Resonance Amplifiers (HRAs), devices developed by Casper Darling that protect their wearers from the effects of the Hiss. Pope explains that the Oldest House is on complete lockdown until the Hiss can be eradicated. Seeking to release the lockdown and access other sectors of the building, Jesse enters the Oldest House's Maintenance Sector and is guided by Ahti to repair the building's electricity and plumbing to prevent a major meltdown. Jesse then uses a Directorial Override to reopen the other sectors, and enters the Research Sector in search of Marshall, whom she believes knows about Dylan. Jesse aids Marshall in retaking the Research Sector and facilitating production of more HRAs. Marshall then reveals that Dylan, known to the Bureau as \"Prime Candidate 6\", was brought in as a candidate for the role of Director due to his special parautilitarian abilities, but after he proved unstable and killed several Bureau agents, he was detained in the Containment Sector. Jesse rushes to the sector to find Dylan, only to learn that he has appeared suddenly in the Executive Sector and surrendered to the FBC agents there. Dylan tells Jesse that he has embraced the Hiss, which he believes will set him free of the Bureau, and that their invasion was made possible by the Slide Projector Object of Power that the Bureau recovered from Ordinary. Dylan warns his sister not to trust Polaris, but Jesse resolves to find and deactivate the Slide Projector.\n\nJesse investigates the Prime Candidate program and learns that both she and Dylan were considered for the role of Director, and that the Slide Projector is contained in the Research Sector. Ahti gives Jesse a [[cassette player]] which enables her to navigate an elaborate maze protecting the Slide Projector's chamber. In the chamber, Jesse finds the Slide Projector missing. She learns that Darling led several expeditions into the [[Parallel universes in fiction|dimension]] accessed through the only surviving slide the FBC was able to recover (the other slides having been burned by Jesse years prior), discovering a polyhedron-shaped organism he named Hedron, which is the source of the HRA resonance. Jesse discovers that Hedron is Polaris, who called out to Jesse to save her from the Hiss; however, when Jesse reaches Hedron's containment chamber, the Hiss attacks and seemingly kills it.\n\nJesse's mind is invaded as the Hedron resonance falters; however, she is able to rediscover Polaris's essence within her and restore control. Jesse learns that Trench fell under the Hiss's influence during one of Darling's expeditions; he stole and concealed a second slide and used it to let the Hiss into the Oldest House to destroy what he perceived to be the threat of Hedron's takeover. Jesse finds the Slide Projector in the Executive Sector and, through it, enters the Astral Plane to confront Dylan, who is attempting to take over the Board through the Hiss. Jesse defeats the defending Hiss and cleanses Dylan, who falls into a coma. Finally accepting her new role as Director, Jesse resolves to defeat the remaining Hiss in order to restore order to the Bureau.\n\n===''The Foundation''===\n''The Foundation'' takes place in an eponymous location at the bottom of the Oldest House, where Jesse is summoned by the Board to deal with a threat to the Bureau. In the Foundation, Jesse discovers a \"Nail\" that acts as a conduit between the Oldest House and the Astral Plane, which has been damaged. The Board grants Jesse a new ability and instructs her to find the Nail's four nodes to repair it; in the process, Jesse searches for the whereabouts of Marshall, who entered the Foundation during the initial Hiss invasion seeking to secure it.\n\nWhile repairing one of the nodes, Jesse suddenly encounters the Former, an extradimensional entity and ex-member of the Board, which grants Jesse an additional ability which the Board had not ordained. The Board is furious, but later calms, and attempts to persuade Jesse not to trust the Former. Jesse repairs the nodes, but tremors occur between the Oldest House and the Astral Plane which threaten to destroy both dimensions. Jesse reaches the base of the Nail, where she finds Marshall possessed by the Hiss, and kills her. With the aid of the Former, Jesse cleanses the Nail.\n\nMarshall's presence reveals through the Hotline that it was she who destroyed the Nail, seeking to prevent the Hiss from taking over the Oldest House through it, and also as a preventative measure against the Board's control. The Board, in response, destroyed Marshall's HRA, allowing her to be possessed by the Hiss. Jesse, with her faith in the Board shattered, resolves to lead the Bureau her own way, but continue letting the Board believe it is in control. As Jesse exits the Foundation, the Former recedes in the distance.\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Control_rtx_example.jpg|thumb|right|''Control'' is one of the first games to support new graphics cards with real-time [[ray tracing (graphics)|ray tracing]]. Here, the bottom image, with ray-tracing turned on, shows reflections of lights and other surfaces in the marble floor, compared to the more traditionally rendered version, shown on top.]]\n''Control'' was developed by [[Remedy Entertainment]]. As their first major release since their [[initial public offering]] in 2017 and separation from [[Microsoft]] as a publishing partner, ''Control'' was developed using more efficient development strategies to keep costs and time low. In contrast to ''[[Alan Wake]]'' and ''[[Quantum Break]]'' which took seven and five years to complete respectively, ''Control'' was completed within three years with a {{GBP|30 million}} budget, lower than the typical costs of a [[triple A (video gaming)|triple-A]] game.<ref name=\"gi.biz people 2019\">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-12-04-people-of-the-year-2019-remedy-entertainment | title = People of the Year 2019: Remedy Entertainment | first= Matthew | last= Handrahan | date = 4 December 2019 | accessdate = 4 December 2019 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref>\n\nMikael Kasurinen, who worked on ''Alan Wake'' (as lead gameplay designer) and ''Quantum Break'' (as lead director), was ''Control''{{'s}} director and [[Sam Lake]] served as the game's writer and creative director alongside narrative lead Anna Megill.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/07/05/remedys-sam-lake-on-21-years-of-game-storytelling-and-transmedia/|title=Remedy\u2019s Sam Lake on 21 years of game storytelling and transmedia|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=5 July 2017|accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/index.php/e3-2018/2018/06/11/remedy-announces-gravity-bending-shooter-control|title=Remedy Announces Gravity-Bending Shooter, Control|first=Brian|last=Shea|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=11 June 2018|accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref> Development of the game began before the release of ''Quantum Break''.<ref name=\"life after xbox\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-05-25-not-the-finnish-remedys-new-age|title=Remedy on life after Xbox exclusivity|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 May 2017|accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref> As they were finishing ''Quantum Break'' and deciding on the next project, Kasurinen recognized that that game rested heavily on [[full motion video]] and other cinematic elements, and suggested they look at a more open-world game where the player would drive what they experienced.<ref name=\"vgc masurinen\">{{cite web | url = https://www.videogameschronicle.com/features/the-best-game-ive-ever-made-how-remedy-made-control/ | title = \u2018The Best Game I\u2019ve Ever Made\u2019: How Remedy Made Control | first = Andy | last= Robinson | date = 27 August 2019 | accessdate = 3 September 2019 | work = [[Video Games Chronicle]] }}</ref> Instead of focusing on creating a large and complex story, Remedy wanted to put more emphasis on creating a game world and universe that is rich enough for players to craft their own stories.<ref name=\"life after xbox\"/> The team still wanted to leave narrative elements for players to discover to help flesh out the world, and added optional documents, audio logs, and live-action video footage that the player could review at their own pace.<ref name=\"usg dlc\"/> Another goal for the team was to create a game that has high replayability.<ref name=\"life after xbox\"/> They still stated that they wanted to make a strong narrative, one that is \"narrowly focused\" according to Kasurinen.<ref name=\"coop\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/features/2016/12/28/14101058/remedy-new-game-p7|title=Why Alan Wake's creators want to make you the storyteller|first=Brian|last=Crecente|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=18 December 2016|accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe first concept down was creating the fictional FBC, a realistic setting that would serve as a basis for paranormal events and a catalyst for events in the story.<ref name=\"vgc masurinen\"/> This enabled them to consider multiple stories they could tell, not just about the player-character but other individuals in the FBC, but this also created the challenge of how to present the stories of the other characters in the open-world format.<ref name=\"vgc masurinen\"/> The gathered writings of the fictional [[SCP Foundation]] (\"Secure, Contain, Protect\") website was a major influence on ''Control''. Stories on SCP Foundation's site are based on singular objects with strange paranormal impacts, and as a whole, they are narratively linked by the common format of reports written by the fictional SCP Foundation, which catalogs and studies the objects. ''Control'' was built atop this, having the various Objects of Power and Altered Items, along with numerous collectable writings about these objects or other stories in line with SCP.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wired.co.uk/article/control-game-scp-foundation | title = The web's creepiest fictional wiki is now a mind-bending video game | first = Aron | last =Garst | date = 27 August 2019 | accessdate = 2 September 2019 | work = [[Wired UK]] }}</ref> They fixed the story in the genre of the [[new weird]], a modern variant of [[weird fiction]] with stories that combine science fiction and fantasy often with a bureaucratic government agency involved in these events. In ''Control'', they reversed the role to make the bureaucracy at the center of the story. Narrative Designer Brooke Maggs stated \"there is an invisible, assailing presence of bureaucracy in the corporate office setting that is in itself, unsettling\".<ref name=\"ign new weird\"/> The mundane features of the Oldest House helped to contrast against the paranormal aspects of the game, thus well-suiting the new weird, according to World Design Director Stuart MacDonald.<ref name=\"ign new weird\"/> The design team's goal in using the new weird approach was not to create terrifying moments as one would do in a horror game, but instead create a continuing sense of dread for the player.<ref name=\"ign new weird\"/>\n\nA further challenge involved creating an environment that would encourage the player to explore, get lost in it, and learn by observation. Kasurinen felt they did not want to include a traditional [[heads-up display]] for the player, with mission markers or other clutter, and instead have the player use mission descriptions in their log and careful observation of the environment to figure out where to go next.<ref name=\"vgc masurinen\"/> This further led to the decision to only tell player critical information via some means, leaving the player to fill in the missing parts with their own observations and imaginations.<ref name=\"vgc masurinen\"/> They also wanted a fluid environment, where nearly any object in it could be used as part of the player-character's telekinetic powers, so that the game world could be both a weapon to be used by the player, or a weapon against the player-character. To achieve this, Remedy replaced the [[Havok (software)|Havok]] physics in their in-house engine with [[PhysX]], and improved their [[artificial intelligence]] to enable enemies to take advantage of these changes.<ref name=\"vgc masurinen\"/>\n\nThe everyday objects that would become Objects of Power in the game also were selected to be within the concept of the new weird. One such Object of Power is a [[floppy disk]]. MacDonald said he was drawn to use a floppy disk in this manner after reading a story about how many of the [[United States national missile defense]] sites had only recently transitioned off floppy disks, and prior to that, these disks could be seen as proverbial weapons that were held with high reverence.<ref name=\"ign new weird\"/> The copious presence in the Oldest House of 1960s and 1970s technology such as [[pneumatic tubes]], [[slide projectors]] and [[monochrome monitor]]s, and the absence of modern-day technologies such as [[cell phones]], is explained in-game as the result of the tendency of newer technologies to fail or malfunction within the boundaries of the Oldest House.\n\n[[File:33_Thomas_Sidewalk_View.JPG|thumb|left|upright|[[AT&T]] [[33 Thomas Street|Long Lines Building]] served as inspiration for the Oldest House.]]\nThe Oldest House setting was based on [[brutalist architecture]], a style utilizing large concrete blocks popularized in the 1950s and used in many government buildings at the time. The game's world design director, Stuart Macdonald, described brutalism as a good science-fiction setting, as it has \"this sense of power, weight, strength and stability to it\", and when the Oldest House's geometries are affected by the Hiss, \"it makes for a really good contrast with the impossible architecture\".<ref name=\"eurog art\">{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-09-03-remedys-control-is-built-on-concrete-foundations | title = Remedy's Control is built on concrete foundations | first = Ewan | last= Wilson | date = 3 September 2019 | accessdate = 4 September 2019 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> The relatively flat colors of the background walls made it an ideal canvas to showcase other design and lighting effects in the game, It also served well into the telekinesis powers of the game, as the concrete walls would be used in lieu of a target object when the player throws debris at foes via telekinesis, and the initially pristine spaces end up showing the results of a large, destructive battle.<ref name=\"eurog art\"/> Among real-world influences in the game's architecture is [[33 Thomas Street]], formerly known as the AT&T Long Lines Building, a windowless building in the center of New York City. Macdonald used this building as a modern example of brutalism, and created the Oldest House as a \"bizarre, brutalist monolith\" to house the FBC.<ref name=\"eurog art\"/> Other real-world locations used as inspiration included the [[Boston City Hall]], the Andrews Building at the [[University of Toronto Scarborough]], and the [[Met Breuer]].<ref name=\"eurog art\"/>\n\nOther real-world architects inspired the game's structures. [[Carlo Scarpa]]'s work was used heavily in designing stairways that ascended with other parts of the structure, while [[Tadao Ando]]'s focus on lighting and spiritual spaces were reflected in other parts of the game.<ref name=\"eurog art\"/> Additionally, the design team turned to film for other inspiration. Films of [[Stanley Kubrick]], particularly ''[[A Clockwork Orange (film)|A Clockwork Orange]]'', as well as films featuring oppressive government agencies, such as ''[[The Shape of Water]]'', served as part of the design basis.<ref name=\"eurog art\"/> Other films, like ''[[Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy (film)|Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy]]'', evoke the concept of repetitiveness, process, and ritualism in these agencies, and that was used to define some of the internal artwork and architecture.<ref name=\"eurog art\"/> Art director Janne Pulkkinen stated they also looked at real world churches and other places where ritualism is common, as lighting and design of those spaces are often used to draw attention to specific points of interest.<ref name=\"eurog art\"/>\n\nCertain areas of the game feature [[full-motion video]] sequences. Most of these are of Dr. Casper Darling explaining parts of the Oldest House and Objects of Power within it, with Darling played by [[Matthew Porretta]]. Another set of videos are short episodes of a fictional show called \"The Threshold Kids\", a puppet-based show seemingly aimed at children that may reside within the Oldest House. \"The Threshold Kids\" were written by narrative lead Anna Megill and produced by their senior cinematic designer Mircea Purdea.<ref name=\"ign new weird\">{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/10/07/control-confronts-us-with-a-very-specific-type-of-horror-a-lack-of-control | title = Control Confronts Us With A Very Specific Type of Horror: A Lack of Control | first= Taurqi | last = Moosa | date = October 7, 2019 | accessdate = October 7, 2019 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref> [[Poets of the Fall]], an alternative rock group that are close friends of Remedy, provided songs for the game, including \"Take Control\", in-game stated to be by the fictional band \"The Old Gods of Asgard\", itself an allusion back to ''Alan Wake''.<ref name=\"gamespot wake connnections\">{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/control-is-full-of-details-about-alan-wakes-fate/2900-3029/ | title = Control Is Full Of Details About Alan Wake's Fate | first = Phil | last = Hornshaw | date = September 23, 2019 | accessdate = October 7, 2019 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref> Remedy used this song as part of the game's \"Ashtray Maze\", a section where Jesse fights through an ever-changing set of room set to the song. Remedy worked with Poets of the Fall so that they could incorporate the song dynamically as the player progressed through sections of this maze <ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/see-how-controls-incredible-ashtray-maze-was-creat/1100-6472494/ | title =See How Control's Incredible Ashtray Maze Was Created | first = Tamoor | last =Hussain | date = January 5, 2020 | accessdate = January 5, 2020 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref>\n\n''Control'' represents one of the first major games to be released after the introduction of [[graphics card]]s that support real time [[ray tracing (graphics)|ray tracing]] (RTX), and considered the first game with a nearly-full implementation of all possible RTX features.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/control-is-the-best-most-complex-implementation-of-ray-tracing-in-a-game-so-far/ | title = Control is the best, most complex implementation of ray tracing in a game so far | first = Jarred | last= Walton | date = 30 August 2019 | accessdate =30 August 2019 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref> The game also supports more standard rendering techniques suitable for less powerful graphical hardware.\n\nThe game includes [[Easter egg (media)|Easter eggs]] referring to ''Alan Wake'', which shares similar paranormal themes with ''Control''; one such Easter egg discusses the aftermath of ''Alan Wake'' as part of the FBC's case files, which considered what happened in Bright Falls, the primary location of ''Alan Wake'', to have been an AWE.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vg247.com/2019/08/27/alan-wake-easter-egg-control/ |title = Here\u2019s the brilliant Alan Wake easter egg in Control and how to find it | first = Kirk | last =McKeand | date = 29 August 2019 | accessdate = 29 August 2019 | work = [[VG247]] }}</ref> A secret area includes a vision of Alan Wake. The past event in the town of Ordinary was alluded to by a [[backmasking]] track in the credits sequence of ''[[Alan Wake: American Nightmare]]'', with an unknown speaker stating \"It will happen again, in another town. A town called Ordinary.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/control-fans-believe-alan-wake-takes-place-in-the-same-1837840844 | title = Control Is Packed With Alan Wake References | first= Gita | last= Jackson | date = 3 September 2019 | accessdate = 3 September 2019 | work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref><ref name=\"gamespot wake connnections\"/> Kasurinen said that the inclusion of such references helps to establish a type of continuity between its games, elements to be found and shared by its player community, but not meant to necessarily establish a shared universe between the games.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.videogameschronicle.com/news/controls-remedy-wants-a-continuity-between-its-games/ | title = Control\u2019s Remedy wants \u2018a continuity\u2019 between its games | first = Andy | last = Robinson | date = 31 August 2019 | accessdate = 3 September 2019 | work = [[Video Games Chronicle]] }}</ref>\n\n===Cast===\nThe game's main voice cast was announced at [[New York Comic Con]] in 2018, consisting of various stars from Remedy's previous games. Courtney Hope, who played the character Beth Wilder in ''[[Quantum Break]]'', stars as Jesse Faden, while [[James McCaffrey (actor)|James McCaffrey]], known for his roles as the title character of ''[[Max Payne]]'' and Thomas Zane in ''[[Alan Wake]]'', plays the role of Zachariah Trench. [[Matthew Porretta]], famous for his role as the titular character of ''[[Alan Wake]]'', is also featured in both voice roles and live-action videos as the character of Dr. Casper Darling.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dwan |first1=Hannah |title=Alan Wake and Max Payne\u2019s voice actors are going to appear in Remedy\u2019s next game, Control |url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/10/15/remedy-control-voice-actors-alan-wake-max-payne/ |website=VG24/7 |accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"usg dlc\"/>\n\nThe game also includes a voice cameo by [[Hideo Kojima]] and his English translator Aki Saito; in one side mission, a recording by Dr. Yoshimi Tokui, voiced by Kojima, relates a dream-like experience in Japanese, with the English translation given by Saito.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2019/8/28/20836789/hideo-kojima-control-easter-egg-voiceover-aki-saito-credits-ps4-pc-xbox-one | title = Hideo Kojima is in Control, narrating a very weird mission | first = Owen | last =Good | date = 28 August 2019 | accessdate = 29 August 2019 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n\n===Marketing and release===\nIn May 2017, Remedy announced that they had partnered with [[505 Games]] to publish the game, then codenamed \"P7\". 505 provided marketing and publishing support and a fund of \u20ac7.75 million to assist the game's development, while Remedy retained the [[intellectual property]] rights to ''Control''. In the press release, Remedy revealed that the game will have complex gameplay mechanics and that it will be a \"longer term experience\" than its previous games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-05-03-505-games-will-publish-remedy-entertainments-new-game|title=505 Games will publish Remedy Entertainment's new game|first=Matthew|last=Handrahan|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=3 May 2018|accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref> ''P7'' was being worked on by Remedy alongside two other projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/remedys-upcoming-third-person-action-game-codenamed-p7-will-be-out-in-2019/|title=Remedy's upcoming third-person action game, codenamed P7, will be out in 2019|first=Samuel|last=Horti|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=18 February 2018|accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref> The game was officially revealed at [[Sony Interactive Entertainment]]'s [[E3 2018]] press conference.<ref name=\"release date\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/396643-e3-2018-new-remedy-game-control|title=E3 2018: New Remedy Game Control Announced at Sony Conference|first=Bradley|last=Russell|work=[[Game Revolution]]|date=11 June 2018|accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the months leading up to the launch of the game, it was featured in a significant campaign as one of the first games to use [[Nvidia|Nvidia's]] [[Ray tracing (graphics)|ray tracing]] features from the company's [[Nvidia RTX|RTX]] graphics cards.<ref>{{Citation|title=Control \u2013 Exclusive New RTX Gameplay Trailer|url=https://www.facebook.com/NVIDIAGeForce/videos/614774169031498/|language=en|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> The game was bundled with sales of graphics cards supporting the RTX technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nvidia.com/en-us/geforce/campaigns/control-wolfenstein-youngblood-bundle/|title=Buy GeForce RTX, Get Games|website=NVIDIA|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> Nvidia created or hosted nine videos, including an exclusive gameplay trailer, to display the game's ray tracing integration.\n\nThe Microsoft Windows version was released on the [[Epic Games Store]] platform; under the terms of this exclusivity, platform operator [[Epic Games]] paid Digital Bros, 505 Games' parent company, {{\u20ac|9.49&nbsp;million|link=yes}} ({{US$|10.5&nbsp;million|link=yes}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-09-20-epic-paid-505-games-parent-over-usd10m-for-control-pc-exclusivity|title=Epic paid 505 Games parent over $10m for Control PC exclusivity|last=Valentine|first=Rebekah|date=20 September 2019|website=GamesIndustry.biz}}</ref>\n\n===Post-release===\nRemedy has affirmed plans for at least two additional content expansions to ''Control'', titled \"The Foundation\" and \"AWE\", both narratively set after the main game with Jesse taking on her role as the FBC Director. However, at the time of ''Control''{{'}}s launch, the specifics of this content had yet to be determined, according to narrative designer Brooke Maggs, as the team's focus was on addressing performance issues for the console version of the games.<ref name=\"usg dlc\">{{cite web | url = https://www.usgamer.net/articles/control-postmortem-exploring-the-story-lore-and-dlc-possibilities-with-remedy | title = Control Postmortem: Exploring the Story, Lore, and DLC Possibilities With Remedy | first= Mike | last= Williams | date =4 September 2019 | accessdate = 5 September 2019 | work = [[USGamer]] }}</ref> \"The Foundation\" is planned for release on 26 March 2020.<ref name=\"first dlc\"/>\n\nAdditional smaller, non-narrative content is also planned.<ref name=\"usg dlc\"/> The first, \"Expeditions\", was released as a free update on 12 December 2019, and presents standalone missions of various difficulty with power-up items for their character.<ref name=\"first dlc\">{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/12/13/control-dlc-out-now-first-expansion-release-date-announced | title = Control DLC Out Now, First Expansion Release Date Announced | first= Matthew | last = Adler | date = December 12, 2019 | accessdate = December 12, 2019 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = (PC) 85/100<ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/control |title=Control for PC Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref><br>(PS4) 82/100<ref name=\"MCPS4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/control |title=Control for PlayStation 4 Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref><br>(XONE) 84/100<ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/control |title=Control for Xbox One Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 9/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Makedonski |first=Brett |date=26 August 2019 |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-control-564466.phtml |title=Review: Control |publisher=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n| EGM = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Goroff |first=Michael |date=26 August 2019 |url=https://egmnow.com/control-review/ |title=Control review |publisher=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n| GI = 8.75/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Reeves |first=Ben |date=26 August 2019 |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/review/control/control-review-a-heady-power-trip |title=Control Review \u2013 A Heady Power Trip |publisher=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n| GameRev = 4.5/5<ref>{{cite web |last=Leri |first=Michael |date=26 August 2019 |url=https://www.gamerevolution.com/review/586665-control-review-ps4 |title=Control Review - Weirdness, perfected |publisher=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Peter |date=26 August 2019 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/control-review-break-on-through-to-the-other-side/1900-6417278/ |title=Control Review - An Action-Packed Paranormal Portal |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Loveridge |first=Sam |date=26 August 2019 |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/control-review-remedy-games/ |title=Control review: \"A game we'll be talking about for generations\" |publisher=[[GamesRadar+]] |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8.8/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Dornbush |first=Jonathan |date=26 August 2019 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/08/26/control-review-2 |title=Control Review |publisher=[[IGN]] |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 88/100<ref>{{cite web |last=Davenport |first=James |date=26 August 2019 |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/control-review/ |title=Control review |publisher=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n| VG = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Wise |first=Josh |date=26 August 2019 |url=https://www.videogamer.com/reviews/control-review |title=Control review |publisher=VideoGamer.com |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{expand section|date=August 2019}}\n\n''Control'' received positive reviews, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MCPC\"/><ref name=\"MCPS4\"/><ref name=\"MCXONE\"/>\n\n''[[IGN]]'' chose ''Control'' as their \"Game of the Year\", along with other awards including \"Best Action-Adventure Game\", \"Best Video Game Art Direction\", and \"Best Video Game Story\".<ref>https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/12/10/best-games-2019<nowiki> IGN Game Awards 2019 | date = December 11, 2019 | accessdate = December 15, 2019 | work = [[IGN]}}</nowiki></ref> ''[[Game Informer]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/video-feature/2019/12/27/why-control-is-game-informers-2019-game-of-the-year|title=Why Control Is Game Informer's 2019 Game Of The Year|last=Vader|first=Leo|website=Game Informer|language=en|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://egmnow.com/egms-game-of-the-year-2019-control/|title=EGM\u2019s Game of the Year 2019: Control|last=Harmon|first=Josh|date=2020-01-01|website=EGM|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> and [[GamesRadar+]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/best-games-2019/3/|title=The 25 best games of 2019|last=Staff 2019-12-20T14:02:15Z|first=GamesRadar|website=gamesradar|language=en|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> awarded ''Control'' as their \"Game of the Year\", while ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/12/12/21004882/control-best-games-of-the-year-goty-2019-remedy|title=GOTY 2019 #2: Control|last=Frushtick|first=Russ|date=2019-12-12|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> and ''[[GameSpot]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/gamespot-game-of-the-year-2019s-10-best-games/2900-3261/7/|title=GameSpot Game Of The Year: 2019's 10 Best Games|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> list ''Control'' among their top 10 games of 2019. ''[[PC Gamer]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/game-of-the-year-awards-2019/|title=Game of the Year Awards 2019|last=Gamer|first=P. C.|date=2019-12-30|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> chose Control as \"Best Setting\" for their Best Games of 2019.\n\n''[[Digital Foundry]]'' and ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' considered ''Control'' on PC to potentially be a \"[[killer app]]\" for Nvidia's RTX graphics cards, citing it as helping to enhance the game's visual style.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/9/2/20844751/control-pc-ray-tracing-video|title=Why Control looks so much better on PC|last=Plante|first=Chris|date=2019-09-02|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-2019-control-pc-a-vision-for-next-gen-rendering|title=Control PC: a vision for the future of real-time rendering?|last=Battaglia|first=Alex|date=2019-08-31|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"1\" | 2018\n| [[Golden Joystick Awards]]\n| Most Wanted Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite news |last=Hoggins |first=Tom |date=24 September 2018 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/news/golden-joysticks-2018-nominees-announced-voting-open-now/ |title=Golden Joysticks 2018 nominees announced, voting open now |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"22\" | 2019\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Game Critics Awards]]\n| Best Original Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Nunneley |first=Stephany |date=27 June 2019 |url=https://www.vg247.com/2019/06/27/e3-2019-game-critics-awards-winners/ |title=E3 2019 Game Critics Awards \u2013 Final Fantasy 7 Remake wins Best of Show |publisher=[[VG247]] |accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best PC Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Action/Adventure Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | Golden Joystick Awards\n| Best Storytelling\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Tailby |first=Stephen |date=20 September 2019 |url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/days_gone_rides_off_with_three_nominations_in_this_years_golden_joystick_awards |title=Days Gone Rides Off with Three Nominations in This Year's Golden Joystick Awards |publisher=Push Square |accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=GamesRadar staff |date=25 October 2019 |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/vote-now-for-your-ultimate-game-of-the-year-in-the-golden-joystick-awards-2019/ |title=Vote now for your Ultimate Game of the Year in the Golden Joystick Awards 2019 |publisher=[[GamesRadar+]] |accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=GamesRadar staff |date=15 November 2019 |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/Golden-Joystick-awards-2019-winners/ |title=Here's every winner from this year's Golden Joystick Awards, including the Ultimate Game of the Year |publisher=[[GamesRadar+]] |accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Visual Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Audio\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Critics' Choice Award\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Ultimate Game of the Year]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[Titanium Awards]]\n| Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/ |title=Titanium Awards 2019 |publisher=[[Fun & Serious Game Festival]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121193654/https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/ |archivedate=21 November 2019 |url-status=live |accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Art\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Game Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Narrative Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Adventure Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Soundtrack <small>(Petri Alanko)</small>\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" | [[The Game Awards 2019]]\n| [[The Game Award for Game of the Year|Game of the Year]]\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Winslow |first=Jeremy |date=19 November 2019 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2019-nominees-full-list/1100-6471564/ |title=The Game Awards 2019 Nominees Full List |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Makuch |first=Eddie |date=13 December 2019 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2019-winners-sekiro-takes-game-of-/1100-6472169/ |title=The Game Awards 2019 Winners: Sekiro Takes Game Of The Year |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Game Direction\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Narrative\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Art Direction\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Best Audio Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Performance <small>(Courtney Hope)</small>\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Performance <small>(Matthew Porretta)</small>\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Action/Adventure Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"45\" | 2020\n| New York Game Awards\n| Great White Way Award for Best Acting in a Game <small>(Courtney Hope)</small>\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Meitzler |first=Ryan |date=22 January 2020 |url=https://www.dualshockers.com/the-new-york-video-game-awards-2020-winners-list/ |title=The New York Video Game Awards 2020 Winners Revealed; The Outer Worlds Takes Game of the Year |publisher=DualShockers |accessdate=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[18th Visual Effects Society Awards|Visual Effects Society Awards]]\n| Outstanding Visual Effects in a Real-Time Project\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Hipes |first=Patrick |date=7 January 2020 |url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/ves-awards-nominations-2020-list-the-lion-king-the-mandalorian-game-of-thrones-1202823016/ |title=VES Awards Nominations: \u2018The Lion King\u2019, \u2018Alita: Battle Angel\u2019, \u2018The Mandalorian\u2019 & \u2018GoT\u2019 Top List |publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pedersen |first1=Erik |last2=Blyth |first2=Antonia |date=29 January 2020 |url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/ves-awards-2020-winners-list-1202846197/ |title=VES Awards: \u2018The Lion King\u2019 & \u2018The Irishman\u2019 Take Top Film Honors \u2013 Winners List |publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" | [[23rd Annual D.I.C.E. Awards]]\n| Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Valentine |first=Rebekah |date=10 January 2020 |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2020-01-10-control-death-stranding-each-receive-eight-dice-2020-nominations-including-game-of-the-year |title=Control, Death Stranding each receive eight DICE 2020 nominations, including Game of the Year |publisher=GamesIndustry.biz |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Van Allen |first=Eric |date=14 February 2020 |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/untitled-goose-game-wins-top-bill-at-the-2020-dice-awards |title=Untitled Goose Game Wins Top Bill at the 2020 D.I.C.E. Awards |publisher=[[Eurogamer|USgamer]] |accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Outstanding Achievement in Art Direction\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Achievement in Character <small>(Jesse Faden)</small>\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Achievement in Game Direction\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Achievement in Original Music Composition\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Achievement in Story\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Technical Achievement\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Action Game of the Year\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" | [[NAVGTR Awards]]\n| [[NAVGTR Award for Game of the Year|Game of the Year]]\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=https://navgtr.org/2019-nominees/ |title=2019 Nominees |publisher=[[NAVGTR Awards|National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] |date=13 January 2020 |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://navgtr.org/2019-winners/ |title=2019 Winners |publisher=[[NAVGTR Awards|National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] |date=24 February 2020 |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Animation, Technical\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Art Direction, Contemporary\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Control Design, 3D\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Direction in a Game Cinema\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Game, Original Action\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Graphics, Technical\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Lighting/Texturing\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | [[20th Game Developers Choice Awards]]\n| [[Game Developers Choice Award for Game of the Year|Game of the Year]]\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |author=Gamasutra staff |date=8 January 2020 |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/356378/Death_Stranding_leads_the_pack_of_2020_Game_Developers_Choice_Awards_nominees.php |title=Death Stranding leads the pack of 2020 Game Developers Choice Awards nominees |publisher=[[Gamasutra]] |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Makuch |first=Eddie |date=18 March 2020 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/untitled-goose-game-wins-another-game-of-the-year-/1100-6474953/ |title=Untitled Goose Game Wins Another Game Of The Year Award |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Audio\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Best Narrative\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Technology\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Game Developers Choice Award for Best Visual Art|Best Visual Art]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | [[SXSW Gaming Awards]]\n| Video Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |author=Grayshadow |date=17 February 2020 |url=https://www.noobfeed.com/news/9773/2020-sxsw-gaming-awards-nominees-revealed |title=2020 SXSW Gaming Awards Nominees Revealed |publisher=NoobFeed |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Grayshadow |date=25 March 2020 |url=https://www.noobfeed.com/news/9991/sxsw-2020-gaming-award-winners-revealed |title=SXSW 2020 Gaming Award Winners Revealed |publisher=Noobfeed |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Most Promising New Intellectual Property\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Excellence in Art\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Excellence in Design\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Excellence in Narrative\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Excellence in Technical Achievement\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Excellence in Visual Achievement\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"11\" | [[16th British Academy Games Awards]]\n| [[British Academy Games Award for Best Game|Best Game]]\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"11\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Stuart |first=Keith |date=3 March 2020 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/games/2020/mar/03/death-stranding-and-control-dominate-bafta-games-awards-nominations |title=Death Stranding and Control dominate Bafta games awards nominations |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Chilton |first=Louis |date=2 April 2020 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/games/news/bafta-games-awards-2020-results-list-winners-outer-wilds-death-stranding-control-disco-elysium-a9444411.html |title=Bafta Games Awards 2020: The results in full |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[British Academy Games Award for Game Design|Game Design]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Animation\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Artistic Achievement\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Audio Achievement\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Music\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Narrative\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Original Property\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[British Academy Games Award for Performer|Performer in a Leading Role]] <small>(Courtney Hope)</small>\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[British Academy Games Award for Performer|Performer in a Supporting Role]] <small>(Martti Suosalo)</small>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[British Academy Games Award for Technical Achievement|Technical Achievement]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 18th Annual G.A.N.G. Awards\n| Best Dialogue\n| {{Pending}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Wilson |first=Kelly |date=13 February 2020 |url=https://www.thehypemagazine.com/2020/02/game-audio-network-guild-announces-18th-annual-g-a-n-g-award-nominees/ |title=Game Audio Network Guild Announces 18th Annual G.A.N.G. Award Nominees |publisher=The Hype Magazine |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Original Instrumental\n| {{Pending}}\n|-\n| Best Original Soundtrack Album\n| {{Pending}}\n|-\n| Best Audio Mix\n| {{Pending}}\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.controlgame.com/}}\n\n{{Remedy Entertainment}}\n\n[[Category:2019 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Third-person shooters]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One X enhanced games]]\n[[Category:505 Games]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Finland]]\n[[Category:Video games set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Remedy Entertainment games]]\n[[Category:Video games about the paranormal]]\n[[Category:Video games about psychic powers]]\n[[Category:Science fiction video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional government investigations of the paranormal]]\n[[Category:Weird fiction video games]]\n[[Category:Video games that support DirectX 12]]\n[[Category:Interactive Achievement Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "Zahid Awais", "label": "safe", "comment": "it is a minor edditing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_(video_game)"}
{"title_page": "Pratt & Whitney R-2800 Double Wasp", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=April 2019}}\n<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n |name= R-2800 Double Wasp \n |image= File:Pratt_%26_Whitney_R-2800_Engine_1.jpg \n |caption= A preserved R-2800 engine at the [[National Museum of the United States Air Force]]\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Engine\n |type= [[Radial engine]]\n |national origin= [[United States]]\n |manufacturer= [[Pratt & Whitney]]\n |first run= 1937<br>First flown May 29, 1940\n |major applications= [[Canadair CL-215]] <br> [[Convair CV-240 family]] <br> [[Douglas A-26 Invader]] <br> [[Douglas DC-6]] <br> [[Grumman F6F Hellcat]] <br> [[Grumman F8F Bearcat]] <br> [[Martin B-26 Marauder]] <br> [[Republic P-47 Thunderbolt]] <br> [[Sikorsky CH-37 Mojave]] <br> [[Vought F4U Corsair]]\n |status = \n |produced = 1939-1960\n |number built = 125,334\n |program cost = \n |unit cost = \n |developed from = \n |developed into =\n |variants with their own articles =\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Pratt & Whitney R-2800 Double Wasp''' is an American twin-row, 18-cylinder, [[air-cooled]] radial [[aircraft engine]] with a [[engine displacement|displacement]] of 2,800&nbsp;in\u00b3 (46&nbsp;L), and is part of the long-lived [[Pratt & Whitney Wasp series|Wasp family of engines]]. \n \nThe R-2800 saw widespread use in many important American aircraft during and after [[World War II]]. During the war years, [[Pratt & Whitney]] continued to develop new ideas to upgrade the engine, including [[water injection (engines)|water injection]] for takeoff in cargo and passenger planes and to give emergency power in combat.\n\n==Design and development==\n\nFirst run in 1937,<ref name=P&W>[http://www.pw.utc.com/about_us/classic_engines/r2800_double_wasp.asp]</ref> near the time that the larger (54.9 litres) competing 18-cylinder [[Wright R-3350 Duplex-Cyclone|Wright Duplex-Cyclone]]'s development had been started (May of that year), the 46-liter displacement R-2800 was first-flown by 1940, one year before the Duplex-Cyclone. The Double Wasp was more powerful than the world's only other modern 18-cylinder engine, the [[Gnome-Rh\u00f4ne 18L]] of 3,442&nbsp;in\u00b3 (56.4&nbsp;L). {{#tag:ref|The American [[Wright R-3350 Duplex-Cyclone|Wright Duplex-Cyclone]] radial of 3,347&nbsp;in\u00b3 (54.86&nbsp;L) was also under development at the time,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.468thbombgroup.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=sPINPiUsDfI%3D&tabid=36&mid=467 |title=B-29 Design/Devemopment - Engines |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=468thbombgroup.org |accessdate=August 1, 2013}}</ref> and promised to be more powerful than either the P&W or Gnome-Rhone radials.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enginehistory.org/NoShortDays/Introduction.pdf |title=No Short Days - The Struggle to Develop the R-2800 \"Double Wasp\" Crankshaft - Introduction |last=McCutcheon |first=Kimble |date= |website= |publisher=enginehistory.org |page=4 |accessdate=August 1, 2013}}</ref>|group=nb}} The Double Wasp was much smaller in displacement than either of the other 18-cylinder designs, and heat dissipation was a greater problem. To enable more efficient cooling, the usual practice of casting or forging the cylinder head cooling fins that had been effective enough for other engine designs was discarded, and instead, much thinner and closer-pitched cooling fins were machined from the solid metal of the head forging. The fins were all cut at the same time by a gang of milling saws, automatically guided as it fed across the head in such a way that the bottom of the grooves rose and fell to make the roots of the fins follow the contour of the head, with the elaborate process substantially increasing the surface area of the fins.<ref name=avhist>[http://www.aviation-history.com/engines/pr-2800.htm Pratt and Whitney R-2800] The Aviation History Online Museum. Retrieved: 23 February 2009.</ref>  The [[Dual ignition|twin]] [[distributor]]s<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.connecticutscorsair.com/OM_Fig_1_R-2800_Three_Quarter_Front_View_of_Engine_R-2800-18W.jpg |title=ConnecticutCorsair.com's R-2800 Overhaul Manual (archived Pratt & Whitney maintenance/overhaul manual for R-2800 Double Wasp) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=ConnecticutCorsair.com |publisher=Connecticut Corsair LLC |access-date=April 23, 2015 |quote=From numbered callouts for photo: \"3. Distributor Housing Cover, 16. Distributor Housing\"}}</ref> on the Double Wasp were prominently mounted on the upper surface of the forward gear reduction housing - with one of the pair of magnetos mounted between them on most models - and almost always prominently visible within a cowling, with the conduits for the spark plug wires emerging from the distributors' cases either directly forward or directly behind them, or on the later C-series R-2800s with the two-piece gear reduction housings, on the \"outboard\" sides of the distributor casings.<ref>[http://static4.businessinsider.com/image/575efe5a91058423008c898f/engines-like-this-18-cylinder-pratt-and-whitney-r-2800-double-wasp-powered-a-huge-variety-of-aircraft-from-fighter-attack-planes-such-as-the-vought-f4u-corsair-and-republic-p-47-to-civilian-airliners-such-as-the-lockheed-constellation.jpg A preserved \"C-Series\" Double Wasp, with the \"outboard\" wire exits from the distributor cases.]</ref>\n\n[[File:Cross Section of a Pratt and Whitney R2800 Double Wasp.JPG|thumb|Cross section of a Pratt & Whitney R-2800 Double Wasp]]\n \nWhen the R-2800 was introduced in 1939, it was capable of producing {{convert|2000|hp|kW|abbr=on}}, for a [[power density|specific power]] value of 0.71&nbsp;hp/in\u00b3 (32.6&nbsp;kW/L). The design of conventional air-cooled radial engines had become so scientific and systematic by then, that the Double Wasp was introduced with a smaller incremental power increase than was typical of earlier engines. Nevertheless, in 1941 the power output of production models increased to {{convert|2100|hp|kW|abbr=on}}, and to {{convert|2400|hp|kW|abbr=on}} late in the war. Even more was coaxed from experimental models, with fan-cooled subtypes like the R-2800-57 producing {{convert|2800|hp|kW|abbr=on}}, but in general the R-2800 was a rather highly developed powerplant right from the beginning.<ref name=avhist/>\n\n[[File:XF4U-1 NACA 1940.jpeg|thumb|right|The first prototype F4U Corsair, the earliest aircraft specifically designed to use the Double Wasp]]\n\nThe R-2800 powered several types of fighters and medium bombers during the war, including the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy's]] [[Vought F4U Corsair]], with the XF4U-1 first prototype Corsair becoming the first airframe to fly (as originally designed) with the Double Wasp<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.f4ucorsair.com/history.html |title=Chance Vought F4U Corsair - XF4U-1 - Genesis |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=f4ucorsair.com |publisher=f4ucorsair.com |accessdate=August 9, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130713093920/http://www.f4ucorsair.com/history.html |archivedate=July 13, 2013 }}</ref> in its XR-2800-4 prototype version on May 29, 1940,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.f4ucorsair.com/history.html |title=Chance Vought F4U Corsair - XF4U-1 - Testing |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=f4ucorsair.com |publisher=f4ucorsair.com |accessdate=August 9, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130713093920/http://www.f4ucorsair.com/history.html |archivedate=July 13, 2013 }}</ref> and the first single-engine American fighter plane to exceed 400&nbsp;mph (640&nbsp;km/h) in level flight during October 1940. The R-2800 also powered the Corsair's naval rival, the [[Grumman F6F Hellcat]], the [[United States Army Air Forces|U.S. Army Air Forces']] [[Republic P-47 Thunderbolt]] (which uniquely, for single-engined aircraft, used a General Electric [[turbocharger]]), the twin-engine [[Martin B-26 Marauder]] and [[Douglas A-26 Invader]], as well as the first purpose-built twin-engine radar-equipped night fighter, the [[Northrop P-61 Black Widow]]. When the US entered the war in December 1941, designs advanced rapidly, and long-established engines such as the Wright Cyclone and Double Wasp were re-rated on fuel of much higher [[octane rating]] ([[Engine knocking|anti-knock]] value) to give considerably more power. By 1944, versions of the R-2800 powering late-model P-47s (and other aircraft) had a rating (experimental) of {{convert|2800|hp|kW|abbr=on}} on [[Octane rating|115-grade]] fuel with water injection.<ref name=avhist/>\n\nAfter World War II, the engine was used in the [[Korean War]], and surplus World War II aircraft powered by the Double Wasp served with other countries well past the Korean War, some being retired as late as the latter part of the 1960s when the aircraft were replaced.<ref name=utc>[http://www.pw.utc.com/vgn-ext-templating/v/index.jsp?vgnextoid=3c6ff3b8f77fb010VgnVCM1000000881000aRCRD Pratt & Whitney R-2800 page] Retrieved: 25 October 2008</ref>\n\n===Peacetime===\nEngines grow in power with development, but a major war demands the utmost performance from engines fitted to aircraft whose life in front-line service was unlikely to exceed 50 hours flying, over a period of only a month or two. In peacetime however, the call was for reliability over a period of perhaps a dozen years, and the R-2800's reliability commended its use for long-range patrol aircraft and for the [[Douglas DC-6]], [[Martin 4-0-4]], and [[Convair 240]] transports. The last two were twin-engine aircraft of size, passenger capacity, and high wing loading comparable to the [[Douglas DC-4|DC-4]] and the first [[Lockheed Constellation|Constellations]].<ref name=avhist/>\n\nToday, three-quarters of a century after the first prototype Double Wasp, it still flies in restored vintage [[warbird]] aircraft displayed at [[air show]]s, and sees service worldwide on aircraft such as the [[Canadair CL-215]] water-bomber. In addition, R-2800s continue to power DC-6 cargo and fuel-carrying aircraft in locations such as [[Alaska]]. A total of 125,334 R-2800 engines were produced between 1939 and 1960.<ref name=P&W/>\n\n==Variants==\nThis is a list of representative R-2800 variants, describing some of the mechanical changes made during development of the Double-Wasp. Power ratings quoted are usually maximum \"military\" power that the engine could generate on takeoff and at altitude: 100 Octane fuel was used, unless otherwise noted.\n\nThe R-2800 was developed and modified into a basic sequence of subtypes, \"A\" through \"E\" series, each of which indicated major internal and external modifications and improvements, such that the \"E\" series engines had very few parts in common with the \"A\".{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n;Note:Suffixes such as '''-S14A-G''' denote engines developed for export to other countries.\n\n''Data from White (Airlife)<ref>White 2001 225-292.</ref> unless otherwise noted:''\n\n===Military===\n;Notes:\nThe dash number for each military type (e.g.: '''-21''') was allocated to identify the complete engine model in accordance with the specification under which the engine was manufactured, thus it did not necessarily indicate the sequence in which the engines were manufactured; for example: the -18W was a \"C\" series engine, built from 1945, whereas the -21 was a \"B\" series engine, built from 1943.\n\nUntil 1940 the armed forces adhered strictly to the convention that engines built for the Army Air Forces used engine model numbers with odd numeric suffixes (e.g.: -5), while those built for the US Navy used even (e.g.: -8). After 1940, however, in the interests of standardization, engines were sometimes built to a joint Army-Navy contract, in which case the engines used a common numeric suffix (e.g.: the -10 was used by both Army and Naval aircraft.)\n\nThe suffix '''W''' e.g.: '''-10W''' denotes a sub-series modified to use [[Water injection (engines)|A.D.I Anti-Detonant Injection or water injection]] equipment, using various mixes of water and [[methanol|methyl alcohol]] (CH<sub>3</sub>OH) injected into the carburetor to increase power for short periods: several models of R-2800s were fitted as standard with A.D.I and did not use the '''W''' suffix.{{#tag:ref|P&W authorised the use of 50% methanol, 50% water or combinations of 60% methyl-40% water; or 25% methyl-25% [[Ethanol|ethyl alcohol]]-50% water; or 60% methol-39% water plus 1% anti-corrosive oil.<ref>White 2001, p. 218.</ref>|group=nb}} Few commercial aircraft used water injection.\n\n''\"A\" Series:''\n* '''R-2800-1'''\n: 1,500&nbsp;hp  (1,118&nbsp;kW) at 2,400&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|7,500|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}. Production prototype of \"A\" series engines with the first flight test July 29, 1939.<ref>White 2001, p. 100.</ref> Single-speed two-stage supercharger. Production = 2 (P&W). Tested in [[Vultee V-11#Variants|Vultee YA-19B]].<ref>White 2001, p. 249.</ref>\n* '''R-2800-5'''\n:1,850&nbsp;hp (1,379&nbsp;kW) at 2,600&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|2,700|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}. Main production \"A\" series engine used in [[Martin B-26 Marauder|Martin B-26A, early B series and XB-26D]] and [[Curtiss C-46 Commando#Variants|Curtiss C-55/XC-46]]. Production = 1,429 (P&W 475, Ford 954.)<ref>White 2001, p. 250.</ref>\n* '''R-2800-39''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n\n''\"B\" Series:''\n[[File:Pratt & Whitney R-2800-21 USAF.jpg|thumb|A preserved \"B Series\" R-2800-21 or -59. The A and B series can be most readily identified by their smooth, single piece nose casings. This photo shows the simplified, tubular [[Ignition system|ignition harness]] fitted to some R-2800 subtypes.{{#tag:ref|The placard on this R-2800, photographed in the [[National Museum of the United States Air Force]] says that this is a -21, built by Ford in 1943: components such as ignition harnesses were interchangeable between the likes of -21 and -59 series engines.|group=nb}}\n]]\n* '''R-2800-8'''\n:2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|1,000|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; 1,800 (1,342&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|15,500|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}. First series production \"B\" Series engine using a two-stage, two-speed supercharger and with internal engineering changes resulting in increased power and reliability. Updraft [[Bendix-Stromberg pressure carburetor|Bendix-Stromberg PT-13D-4 pressure carburetor]]. First production engines delivered to [[United States Navy|U.S.N]] November 11, 1941. Used in [[Vought F4U Corsair#Variants|Brewster F3A-1, Goodyear FG-1, Vought F4U-1 and F4U-2]]. Production = 3,903 (P&W 2,194; Nash 1,709.)<ref name=\"White 2001, pp. 251-252\">White 2001, pp. 251-252.</ref>\n* '''R-2800-8W'''\n:2,250&nbsp;hp (1,677&nbsp;kW) [[War emergency power#WEP in WWII aircraft|WEP]] with water injection. First production engine using ADI equipment, major production version of -8 and used in some versions of F4U Corsair. Production = 8,668 (P&W 5,574; Nash 3,094.)<ref name=\"White 2001, pp. 251-252\"/>\n* '''R-2800-10''' and '''R-2800-10W'''\n:2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|1,000|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; 1,800 (1,342&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|15,500|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; up to 2,250&nbsp;hp (1,677&nbsp;kW) WEP with water injection. Similar to -8 series apart from downdraft PT-13G2-10 and PT-13G6-10 (-10W) carburetor. Used in [[Curtiss P-60#Variants|Curtiss XP-60E]], [[Grumman F6F Hellcat#Variants|Grumman F6F-3 (-10; late production -10W) and F6F-5 (-10W) series]]  and [[Northrop P-61 Black Widow|Northrop XP-61, YP-61, and P-61A-1.]] Production = 4,621 -10 (P&W 2,931; Nash 1,690) and 12,940 -10W (P&W 3,040; Nash 9,900); Total = 17,561.<ref name=\"White 2001, pp. 251-252\"/>\n* '''R-2800-21'''\n:2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|2,500|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|25,000|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}. First production variant fed by a [[General Electric]] C-1 [[Turbocharger|turbosupercharger]].<ref>Bodie 1994, p. 387.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Prototype and production prototypes were the \"A\" series R-2800-17 (one built) and R-2800-35 (11 built), fitted to the XP-47B and early P-47Bs respectively.<ref>White 2001, pp. 257, 269, 387.</ref>|group=nb}} Designed for use in the [[Republic P-47 Thunderbolt#Development|Republic P-47B, C, D, G and XP-47F and K]]. Production = 5,720 (P&W 1,049; Ford 4,671.)<ref>White 2001, p. 260.</ref>\n* '''R-2800-25''' -  2,000&nbsp;hp (1,490&nbsp;kW) \u2014 for [[Northrop P-61 Black Widow]]\n* '''R-2800-27''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-31''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-41''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-43''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-51''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-59'''\n:2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|2,500|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW) at 2,500&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|25,000|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; 2,300&nbsp;hp (1,700&nbsp;kW) WEP with water injection. Main production variant used in P-47 series, fed by an improved C-23 turbosupercharger.<ref>Bodie 1994, p. 392.</ref> Differed from -21 in being fitted with A.D.I and a General Electric ignition system with a simplified, tubular ignition harness developed by the Scinitilla company in partnership with Bendix. Used in P-47C and D, XP-47L. Production = 11,391 (P&W 592; Ford 10,799).<ref name=\"Wh280\">White 2001, p. 280.</ref> {{#tag:ref|'''R-2800-63''' with small manufacturing differences was interchangeable with -21 or -59 . Production =2,092 (P&W 1,262; Ford 767).<ref name=\"Wh280\"/>|group=nb}}\n* '''R-2800-59W''' - 2,500&nbsp;hp (1,890&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-65''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-65W''' - 2,250&nbsp;hp (1,677&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-71''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-75''' - 2,200&nbsp;hp (1,640&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-79''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n\n''\"C\" Series''\n[[File:HARP Pratt & Whitney R-2800 Double Wasp.JPG|thumb|A \"C Series\" R-2800, with the two section nose casing incorporating torque-monitoring equipment and a Spark Advance unit, with the \"outboard\" sparkplug wiring conduit location for each of the twin enclosed distributors.]]\n\n* '''R-2800-18W'''\n:2,100&nbsp;hp (1,566&nbsp;kW) at 2,800&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|1,000|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; 1,800&nbsp;hp (1,342&nbsp;kW) at 2,800&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|25,500|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>USN history 1986, p. 8.</ref> First series production variant of the \"C\" Series, which was a complete redesign of the R-2800. Some of the main changes were [[Forge#Drop forging|forged]], rather than [[Continuous casting|cast]] cylinders, allowing an increased compression ratio (from 6.65:1 to 6.75:1), a redesigned crankshaft, a single piece, rather than split crankcase center section, and a two section nose casing, incorporating hydraulically operated [[Dynamometer#Hydraulic brake|torque-monitoring]] equipment and an automatic, vacuum operated [[Ignition timing#Vacuum timing advance|spark-advance]] unit.<ref>White 2001, pp. 163-165, 167-169.</ref> The supercharger used [[fluid coupling]] for the second stage.<ref>White 2001, pp. 144-145, 148-152, 158-160.</ref> Updraft Bendix-Stromberg PT-13G2-10 carburetor. Used in [[Vought F4U Corsair#F4U-4|Vought F4U-4 and -4 variants]].{{#tag:ref|Because the \"C\" series engines ran more smoothly than previous R-2800s the F4U-4 was able to use simplified, solid engine mountings rather than needing mountings incorporating shock absorbers.<ref>White 2001, pp. 432, 437.</ref>|group=nb}} Production = 3,257 (P&W).<ref>White 2001, p. 257.</ref>\n\n* '''R-2800-22W''' - 2,400&nbsp;hp (1,789&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-34''' - 2,100&nbsp;hp (1,567&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-34W''' - 2,100&nbsp;hp<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.ww2aircraft.net/forum/engines/terminology-engine-data-36560-3.html#post1006503 |title = Terminology and engine data}}</ref> (1,567&nbsp;kW), 2,400&nbsp;hp (1,789&nbsp;kW) with water-methanol injection\n* '''R-2800-44''' - 2,300&nbsp;hp (1,700&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-44W''' - 2,400&nbsp;hp (1,789&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-48''' - 2,500&nbsp;hp (1,890&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-48W''' - 2,400&nbsp;hp (1,789&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-54''' - 2,100&nbsp;hp (1,567&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-57''' - 2,800&nbsp;hp (2,090&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-57C''' - 2,800&nbsp;hp (2,090&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-73''' - 2,800&nbsp;hp (2,090&nbsp;kW) \u2014 with General Electric CH-5-A3 turbocharger<ref>[https://aviationshoppe.com/manuals/wwii_aircraft_superchargers/wwii_aircraft_turbosupercharger.html GE Turbocharger Manual \"Section XIX\" for its CH-5 series turbochargers, pgs. 206-209]</ref> for P-61C Black Widow\n* '''R-2800-77''' - 2,800&nbsp;hp (2,090&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-83''' - 2,100&nbsp;hp (1,567&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-83AM''' - 2,100&nbsp;hp (1,567&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-99W''' - 2,300&nbsp;hp (1,700&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-103W''' - 2,500&nbsp;hp (1,890&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-2SB-G''' - 1,850&nbsp;hp (1,379&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-CB16''' - 2,400&nbsp;hp (1,789&nbsp;kW), 2,500&nbsp;hp (1,890&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-CB17''' - 2,500&nbsp;hp (1,890&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-S1A4-G''' - 1,850&nbsp;hp (1,379&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-S1C3-G''' - 2,100&nbsp;hp (1,567&nbsp;kW)\n\n''\"D\" Series:''\n* '''R-2800-23''' - 2,200&nbsp;hp (1,640&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-29''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n\n''\"E\" Series:''\n* '''R-2800-30W ''' - 2,250&nbsp;hp (1,677&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-32W ''' - 2,450&nbsp;hp (1,827&nbsp;kW), 2,850&nbsp;hp (2,125&nbsp;kW) with water-methanol injection\n\n==Applications==\n[[File:B26-dinah-might-899.jpg|Martin B-26 Marauder|thumb|right]]\nThe following is a partial list of aircraft that were powered by the R-2800 (and a few prototypes that utilized it at one point):\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Brewster XA-32]]\n* [[Breguet Deux-Ponts]]\n* [[Canadair CL-215]]\n* [[Canadair North Star|Canadair C-5 North Star]]\n* [[Consolidated TBY Sea Wolf]]\n* [[Convair CV-240 family|Convair 240, 340, and 440]]\n* [[Curtiss P-60]]\n* [[Curtiss XF15C]]\n* [[Curtiss C-46 Commando]]\n* [[Douglas A-26 Invader]]\n* [[Douglas DC-6]]\n* [[Fairchild C-82 Packet]]\n* [[Fairchild C-123 Provider]]\n* [[Grumman AF Guardian]]\n* [[Grumman F6F Hellcat]]\n* [[Grumman F7F Tigercat]]\n* [[Grumman F8F Bearcat]]\n* [[Howard 500]]\n* [[Lockheed Ventura|Lockheed Ventura/B-34 Lexington/PV-1 Ventura/PV-2 Harpoon]]\n* [[Lockheed C-69 Constellation|Lockheed XC-69E Constellation]]\n* [[Martin B-26 Marauder]]\n* [[Martin PBM-5 Mariner]]\n* [[Martin 2-0-2]]\n* [[Martin 4-0-4]]\n* [[North American AJ Savage]]\n* [[North American XB-28]]\n* [[Northrop XP-56 Black Bullet]]\n* [[Northrop P-61 Black Widow]]\n* [[Northrop F-15 Reporter]]\n* [[Republic P-47 Thunderbolt]]\n* [[Sikorsky CH-37 Mojave]]\n* [[Sikorsky S-60]]\n* [[Vickers Warwick]]\n* [[Vought F4U Corsair]]\n* [[Vultee A-19|Vultee YA-19B]]\n}}\n\n==Engines on display==\n* There is an R-2800-39 on display at the [[New England Air Museum]], [[Bradley International Airport]], Windsor Locks, CT.<ref>http://neam.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&layout=edit&id=1093 \"Pratt & Whitney R-2800-39 Double Wasp\"</ref>\n* An R-2800 used on [[Finnair]] [[Convair Metropolitan]] is on public display at [[Helsinki Airport]].{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n* An R-2800 Double Wasp is on display at the Aerospace Discovery at the [[Florida Air Museum]].{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n* An R-2800 Double Wasp manufactured by Ford Motor Company is on display at the [[Yankee Air Museum]] [[Belleville, Michigan]]<ref>Yankee Air Museum archives and floor display</ref>\n* An R-2800-8W Double Wasp is on display at the [[Flying Leatherneck Aviation Museum]] at [[MCAS Miramar]], [[California]].\n* An R-2800 Double Wasp moving cut-away is on display at the [[USS Midway Museum]] at [[San Diego]], [[California]].\n* An R-2800 Double Wasp is on display at (The National Museum of WWII Aviation) located in (Colorado Springs, Colorado).\n* An R-2800-34 Double Wasp is on public at the [[Aerospace Museum of California]].\n\n==Specifications (R-2800-54)==\n[[File:Pratt-Whitney R-2800.jpg|thumb|right|{{nowrap|Pratt & Whitney R-2800}}]]\n{{pistonspecs\n|<!-- If you do not understand how to use this template, please ask at [[Wikipedia talk:WikiProject Aircraft]] -->\n<!-- Please include units where appropriate (main comes first, alt in parentheses). If data are missing, leave the parameter blank (do not delete it). For additional lines, end your alt units with </li> and start a new, fully-formatted line with <li> -->\n|type=18-cylinder air-cooled twin-row [[radial engine]] with water injection\n|ref=FAA TCDS<ref>[http://www.airweb.faa.gov/Regulatory_and_Guidance_Library%5CrgMakeModel.nsf/0/CF0F9435E20432008525676A006759E7/$FILE/5E-8.pdf FAA Type Certificate Data Sheet] Retrieved: 30 October 2008</ref>\n|bore=5.75 in (146.05 mm)\n|stroke=6 in (152.4 mm)\n|displacement=2,804.5 in\u00b3 (45.96 L) \n|length=81.4 in (2,068 mm)\n|diameter=52.8 in (1,342 mm)\n|width=\n|height=\n|weight=2,360 lb (1,073 kg)\n|valvetrain=[[Poppet valve|Poppet]], two valves per cylinder\n|supercharger=Variable-speed (in F8F-2, unified with throttle via AEC automatic engine control), single-stage single-speed [[centrifugal type supercharger]]\n|turbocharger=\n|fuelsystem=One [[Stromberg (Carburetor brandname)|Stromberg]] [[Pressure carburetor|injection carburetor]]\n|fueltype=100/130 [[Octane rating|octane]] gasoline\n|oilsystem=\n|coolingsystem=Air-cooled\n|power=2,100 hp (1,567 kW) @ 2,700 rpm \n|specpower=0.75 hp/in\u00b3 (34.1 kW/L)\n|compression=\n|fuelcon=\n|specfuelcon=\n|oilcon=\n|power/weight=0.89 hp/lb (1.46 kW/kg)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Aircontent\n|related=\n* [[Pratt & Whitney Wasp]] series\n* [[Pratt & Whitney R-985 Wasp Junior]] \n* [[Pratt & Whitney R-1340 Wasp]] \n* [[Pratt & Whitney R-1535 Twin Wasp Junior]] \n* [[Pratt & Whitney R-1830 Twin Wasp]] \n* [[Pratt & Whitney R-2000 Twin Wasp]] \n* [[Pratt & Whitney R-4360 Wasp Major]]\n|similar engines=\n* [[Alfa Romeo 135]]\n* [[BMW 802]]\n* [[Bristol Centaurus]]\n* [[Fiat A.80]]\n* [[Fiat A.82]]\n* [[Gnome-Rh\u00f4ne 18L]]\n* [[Nakajima Homare]]\n* [[Shvetsov ASh-73]]\n* [[Wright R-3350]]\n\n|lists=\n* [[List of aircraft engines]]\n|see also=\n}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Bodie, Warren M. ''Republic's P-47 Thunderbolt: From Seversky to Victory''. Hayesville, North Carolina: Widewing Publications, 1994. {{ISBN|0-9629359-1-3}}\n*Gunston, Bill. ''World Encyclopedia of Aero Engines: From the Pioneers to the Present Day''. 5th edition, Stroud, UK: Sutton, 2006.{{ISBN|0-7509-4479-X}}\n*{{Ref Jane's|||1951}}\n*White, Graham. ''Allied Aircraft Piston Engines of World War II: History and Development of Frontline Aircraft Piston Engines Produced by Great Britain and the United States During World War II''. Warrendale, Pennsylvania: SAE International, 1995. {{ISBN|1-56091-655-9}}\n*White, Graham. ''R-2800: Pratt & Whitney's Dependable Masterpiece''. Shrewsbury, UK: Airlife Publishing, 2001. {{ISBN|1-84037-335-0}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pratt & Whitney R-2800}}\n* [http://www.pw.utc.com/R2800_Double_Wasp_Engine Pratt & Whitney's R-2800 page]\n* [http://www.aviation-history.com/engines/pr-2800.htm The Aviation History Online Museum's Double Wasp page]\n\n{{P&W piston engines}}\n{{US military piston aeroengines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pratt and Whitney R-2800 Double Wasp}}\n[[Category:Radial engines]]\n[[Category:Pratt & Whitney aircraft engines|R-2800]]\n[[Category:1930s aircraft piston engines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=April 2019}}\n<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n |name= R-2800 Double Wasp \n |image= File:Pratt_%26_Whitney_R-2800_Engine_1.jpg \n |caption= A preserved R-2800 engine at the [[National Museum of the United States Air Force]]\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Engine\n |type= [[Radial engine]]\n |national origin= [[United States]]\n |manufacturer= [[Pratt & Whitney]]\n |first run= 1937<br>First flown May 29, 1940\n |major applications= [[Canadair CL-215]] <br> [[Convair CV-240 family]] <br> [[Douglas A-26 Invader]] <br> [[Douglas DC-6]] <br> [[Grumman F6F Hellcat]] <br> [[Martin B-26 Marauder]] <br> [[Republic P-47 Thunderbolt]] <br> [[Sikorsky CH-37 Mojave]] <br> [[Vought F4U Corsair]]\n |status = \n |produced = 1939-1960\n |number built = 125,334\n |program cost = \n |unit cost = \n |developed from = \n |developed into =\n |variants with their own articles =\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Pratt & Whitney R-2800 Double Wasp''' is an American twin-row, 18-cylinder, [[air-cooled]] radial [[aircraft engine]] with a [[engine displacement|displacement]] of 2,800&nbsp;in\u00b3 (46&nbsp;L), and is part of the long-lived [[Pratt & Whitney Wasp series|Wasp family of engines]]. \n \nThe R-2800 saw widespread use in many important American aircraft during and after [[World War II]]. During the war years, [[Pratt & Whitney]] continued to develop new ideas to upgrade the engine, including [[water injection (engines)|water injection]] for takeoff in cargo and passenger planes and to give emergency power in combat.\n\n==Design and development==\n\nFirst run in 1937,<ref name=P&W>[http://www.pw.utc.com/about_us/classic_engines/r2800_double_wasp.asp]</ref> near the time that the larger (54.9 litres) competing 18-cylinder [[Wright R-3350 Duplex-Cyclone|Wright Duplex-Cyclone]]'s development had been started (May of that year), the 46-liter displacement R-2800 was first-flown by 1940, one year before the Duplex-Cyclone. The Double Wasp was more powerful than the world's only other modern 18-cylinder engine, the [[Gnome-Rh\u00f4ne 18L]] of 3,442&nbsp;in\u00b3 (56.4&nbsp;L). {{#tag:ref|The American [[Wright R-3350 Duplex-Cyclone|Wright Duplex-Cyclone]] radial of 3,347&nbsp;in\u00b3 (54.86&nbsp;L) was also under development at the time,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.468thbombgroup.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=sPINPiUsDfI%3D&tabid=36&mid=467 |title=B-29 Design/Devemopment - Engines |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=468thbombgroup.org |accessdate=August 1, 2013}}</ref> and promised to be more powerful than either the P&W or Gnome-Rhone radials.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enginehistory.org/NoShortDays/Introduction.pdf |title=No Short Days - The Struggle to Develop the R-2800 \"Double Wasp\" Crankshaft - Introduction |last=McCutcheon |first=Kimble |date= |website= |publisher=enginehistory.org |page=4 |accessdate=August 1, 2013}}</ref>|group=nb}} The Double Wasp was much smaller in displacement than either of the other 18-cylinder designs, and heat dissipation was a greater problem. To enable more efficient cooling, the usual practice of casting or forging the cylinder head cooling fins that had been effective enough for other engine designs was discarded, and instead, much thinner and closer-pitched cooling fins were machined from the solid metal of the head forging. The fins were all cut at the same time by a gang of milling saws, automatically guided as it fed across the head in such a way that the bottom of the grooves rose and fell to make the roots of the fins follow the contour of the head, with the elaborate process substantially increasing the surface area of the fins.<ref name=avhist>[http://www.aviation-history.com/engines/pr-2800.htm Pratt and Whitney R-2800] The Aviation History Online Museum. Retrieved: 23 February 2009.</ref>  The [[Dual ignition|twin]] [[distributor]]s<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.connecticutscorsair.com/OM_Fig_1_R-2800_Three_Quarter_Front_View_of_Engine_R-2800-18W.jpg |title=ConnecticutCorsair.com's R-2800 Overhaul Manual (archived Pratt & Whitney maintenance/overhaul manual for R-2800 Double Wasp) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=ConnecticutCorsair.com |publisher=Connecticut Corsair LLC |access-date=April 23, 2015 |quote=From numbered callouts for photo: \"3. Distributor Housing Cover, 16. Distributor Housing\"}}</ref> on the Double Wasp were prominently mounted on the upper surface of the forward gear reduction housing - with one of the pair of magnetos mounted between them on most models - and almost always prominently visible within a cowling, with the conduits for the spark plug wires emerging from the distributors' cases either directly forward or directly behind them, or on the later C-series R-2800s with the two-piece gear reduction housings, on the \"outboard\" sides of the distributor casings.<ref>[http://static4.businessinsider.com/image/575efe5a91058423008c898f/engines-like-this-18-cylinder-pratt-and-whitney-r-2800-double-wasp-powered-a-huge-variety-of-aircraft-from-fighter-attack-planes-such-as-the-vought-f4u-corsair-and-republic-p-47-to-civilian-airliners-such-as-the-lockheed-constellation.jpg A preserved \"C-Series\" Double Wasp, with the \"outboard\" wire exits from the distributor cases.]</ref>\n\n[[File:Cross Section of a Pratt and Whitney R2800 Double Wasp.JPG|thumb|Cross section of a Pratt & Whitney R-2800 Double Wasp]]\n \nWhen the R-2800 was introduced in 1939, it was capable of producing {{convert|2000|hp|kW|abbr=on}}, for a [[power density|specific power]] value of 0.71&nbsp;hp/in\u00b3 (32.6&nbsp;kW/L). The design of conventional air-cooled radial engines had become so scientific and systematic by then, that the Double Wasp was introduced with a smaller incremental power increase than was typical of earlier engines. Nevertheless, in 1941 the power output of production models increased to {{convert|2100|hp|kW|abbr=on}}, and to {{convert|2400|hp|kW|abbr=on}} late in the war. Even more was coaxed from experimental models, with fan-cooled subtypes like the R-2800-57 producing {{convert|2800|hp|kW|abbr=on}}, but in general the R-2800 was a rather highly developed powerplant right from the beginning.<ref name=avhist/>\n\n[[File:XF4U-1 NACA 1940.jpeg|thumb|right|The first prototype F4U Corsair, the earliest aircraft specifically designed to use the Double Wasp]]\n\nThe R-2800 powered several types of fighters and medium bombers during the war, including the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy's]] [[Vought F4U Corsair]], with the XF4U-1 first prototype Corsair becoming the first airframe to fly (as originally designed) with the Double Wasp<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.f4ucorsair.com/history.html |title=Chance Vought F4U Corsair - XF4U-1 - Genesis |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=f4ucorsair.com |publisher=f4ucorsair.com |accessdate=August 9, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130713093920/http://www.f4ucorsair.com/history.html |archivedate=July 13, 2013 }}</ref> in its XR-2800-4 prototype version on May 29, 1940,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.f4ucorsair.com/history.html |title=Chance Vought F4U Corsair - XF4U-1 - Testing |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=f4ucorsair.com |publisher=f4ucorsair.com |accessdate=August 9, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130713093920/http://www.f4ucorsair.com/history.html |archivedate=July 13, 2013 }}</ref> and the first single-engine American fighter plane to exceed 400&nbsp;mph (640&nbsp;km/h) in level flight during October 1940. The R-2800 also powered the Corsair's naval rival, the [[Grumman F6F Hellcat]], the [[United States Army Air Forces|U.S. Army Air Forces']] [[Republic P-47 Thunderbolt]] (which uniquely, for single-engined aircraft, used a General Electric [[turbocharger]]), the twin-engine [[Martin B-26 Marauder]] and [[Douglas A-26 Invader]], as well as the first purpose-built twin-engine radar-equipped night fighter, the [[Northrop P-61 Black Widow]]. When the US entered the war in December 1941, designs advanced rapidly, and long-established engines such as the Wright Cyclone and Double Wasp were re-rated on fuel of much higher [[octane rating]] ([[Engine knocking|anti-knock]] value) to give considerably more power. By 1944, versions of the R-2800 powering late-model P-47s (and other aircraft) had a rating (experimental) of {{convert|2800|hp|kW|abbr=on}} on [[Octane rating|115-grade]] fuel with water injection.<ref name=avhist/>\n\nAfter World War II, the engine was used in the [[Korean War]], and surplus World War II aircraft powered by the Double Wasp served with other countries well past the Korean War, some being retired as late as the latter part of the 1960s when the aircraft were replaced.<ref name=utc>[http://www.pw.utc.com/vgn-ext-templating/v/index.jsp?vgnextoid=3c6ff3b8f77fb010VgnVCM1000000881000aRCRD Pratt & Whitney R-2800 page] Retrieved: 25 October 2008</ref>\n\n===Peacetime===\nEngines grow in power with development, but a major war demands the utmost performance from engines fitted to aircraft whose life in front-line service was unlikely to exceed 50 hours flying, over a period of only a month or two. In peacetime however, the call was for reliability over a period of perhaps a dozen years, and the R-2800's reliability commended its use for long-range patrol aircraft and for the [[Douglas DC-6]], [[Martin 4-0-4]], and [[Convair 240]] transports. The last two were twin-engine aircraft of size, passenger capacity, and high wing loading comparable to the [[Douglas DC-4|DC-4]] and the first [[Lockheed Constellation|Constellations]].<ref name=avhist/>\n\nToday, three-quarters of a century after the first prototype Double Wasp, it still flies in restored vintage [[warbird]] aircraft displayed at [[air show]]s, and sees service worldwide on aircraft such as the [[Canadair CL-215]] water-bomber. In addition, R-2800s continue to power DC-6 cargo and fuel-carrying aircraft in locations such as [[Alaska]]. A total of 125,334 R-2800 engines were produced between 1939 and 1960.<ref name=P&W/>\n\n==Variants==\nThis is a list of representative R-2800 variants, describing some of the mechanical changes made during development of the Double-Wasp. Power ratings quoted are usually maximum \"military\" power that the engine could generate on takeoff and at altitude: 100 Octane fuel was used, unless otherwise noted.\n\nThe R-2800 was developed and modified into a basic sequence of subtypes, \"A\" through \"E\" series, each of which indicated major internal and external modifications and improvements, such that the \"E\" series engines had very few parts in common with the \"A\".{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n;Note:Suffixes such as '''-S14A-G''' denote engines developed for export to other countries.\n\n''Data from White (Airlife)<ref>White 2001 225-292.</ref> unless otherwise noted:''\n\n===Military===\n;Notes:\nThe dash number for each military type (e.g.: '''-21''') was allocated to identify the complete engine model in accordance with the specification under which the engine was manufactured, thus it did not necessarily indicate the sequence in which the engines were manufactured; for example: the -18W was a \"C\" series engine, built from 1945, whereas the -21 was a \"B\" series engine, built from 1943.\n\nUntil 1940 the armed forces adhered strictly to the convention that engines built for the Army Air Forces used engine model numbers with odd numeric suffixes (e.g.: -5), while those built for the US Navy used even (e.g.: -8). After 1940, however, in the interests of standardization, engines were sometimes built to a joint Army-Navy contract, in which case the engines used a common numeric suffix (e.g.: the -10 was used by both Army and Naval aircraft.)\n\nThe suffix '''W''' e.g.: '''-10W''' denotes a sub-series modified to use [[Water injection (engines)|A.D.I Anti-Detonant Injection or water injection]] equipment, using various mixes of water and [[methanol|methyl alcohol]] (CH<sub>3</sub>OH) injected into the carburetor to increase power for short periods: several models of R-2800s were fitted as standard with A.D.I and did not use the '''W''' suffix.{{#tag:ref|P&W authorised the use of 50% methanol, 50% water or combinations of 60% methyl-40% water; or 25% methyl-25% [[Ethanol|ethyl alcohol]]-50% water; or 60% methol-39% water plus 1% anti-corrosive oil.<ref>White 2001, p. 218.</ref>|group=nb}} Few commercial aircraft used water injection.\n\n''\"A\" Series:''\n* '''R-2800-1'''\n: 1,500&nbsp;hp  (1,118&nbsp;kW) at 2,400&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|7,500|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}. Production prototype of \"A\" series engines with the first flight test July 29, 1939.<ref>White 2001, p. 100.</ref> Single-speed two-stage supercharger. Production = 2 (P&W). Tested in [[Vultee V-11#Variants|Vultee YA-19B]].<ref>White 2001, p. 249.</ref>\n* '''R-2800-5'''\n:1,850&nbsp;hp (1,379&nbsp;kW) at 2,600&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|2,700|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}. Main production \"A\" series engine used in [[Martin B-26 Marauder|Martin B-26A, early B series and XB-26D]] and [[Curtiss C-46 Commando#Variants|Curtiss C-55/XC-46]]. Production = 1,429 (P&W 475, Ford 954.)<ref>White 2001, p. 250.</ref>\n* '''R-2800-39''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n\n''\"B\" Series:''\n[[File:Pratt & Whitney R-2800-21 USAF.jpg|thumb|A preserved \"B Series\" R-2800-21 or -59. The A and B series can be most readily identified by their smooth, single piece nose casings. This photo shows the simplified, tubular [[Ignition system|ignition harness]] fitted to some R-2800 subtypes.{{#tag:ref|The placard on this R-2800, photographed in the [[National Museum of the United States Air Force]] says that this is a -21, built by Ford in 1943: components such as ignition harnesses were interchangeable between the likes of -21 and -59 series engines.|group=nb}}\n]]\n* '''R-2800-8'''\n:2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|1,000|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; 1,800 (1,342&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|15,500|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}. First series production \"B\" Series engine using a two-stage, two-speed supercharger and with internal engineering changes resulting in increased power and reliability. Updraft [[Bendix-Stromberg pressure carburetor|Bendix-Stromberg PT-13D-4 pressure carburetor]]. First production engines delivered to [[United States Navy|U.S.N]] November 11, 1941. Used in [[Vought F4U Corsair#Variants|Brewster F3A-1, Goodyear FG-1, Vought F4U-1 and F4U-2]]. Production = 3,903 (P&W 2,194; Nash 1,709.)<ref name=\"White 2001, pp. 251-252\">White 2001, pp. 251-252.</ref>\n* '''R-2800-8W'''\n:2,250&nbsp;hp (1,677&nbsp;kW) [[War emergency power#WEP in WWII aircraft|WEP]] with water injection. First production engine using ADI equipment, major production version of -8 and used in some versions of F4U Corsair. Production = 8,668 (P&W 5,574; Nash 3,094.)<ref name=\"White 2001, pp. 251-252\"/>\n* '''R-2800-10''' and '''R-2800-10W'''\n:2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|1,000|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; 1,800 (1,342&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|15,500|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; up to 2,250&nbsp;hp (1,677&nbsp;kW) WEP with water injection. Similar to -8 series apart from downdraft PT-13G2-10 and PT-13G6-10 (-10W) carburetor. Used in [[Curtiss P-60#Variants|Curtiss XP-60E]], [[Grumman F6F Hellcat#Variants|Grumman F6F-3 (-10; late production -10W) and F6F-5 (-10W) series]]  and [[Northrop P-61 Black Widow|Northrop XP-61, YP-61, and P-61A-1.]] Production = 4,621 -10 (P&W 2,931; Nash 1,690) and 12,940 -10W (P&W 3,040; Nash 9,900); Total = 17,561.<ref name=\"White 2001, pp. 251-252\"/>\n* '''R-2800-21'''\n:2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|2,500|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|25,000|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}. First production variant fed by a [[General Electric]] C-1 [[Turbocharger|turbosupercharger]].<ref>Bodie 1994, p. 387.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Prototype and production prototypes were the \"A\" series R-2800-17 (one built) and R-2800-35 (11 built), fitted to the XP-47B and early P-47Bs respectively.<ref>White 2001, pp. 257, 269, 387.</ref>|group=nb}} Designed for use in the [[Republic P-47 Thunderbolt#Development|Republic P-47B, C, D, G and XP-47F and K]]. Production = 5,720 (P&W 1,049; Ford 4,671.)<ref>White 2001, p. 260.</ref>\n* '''R-2800-25''' -  2,000&nbsp;hp (1,490&nbsp;kW) \u2014 for [[Northrop P-61 Black Widow]]\n* '''R-2800-27''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-31''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-41''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-43''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-51''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-59'''\n:2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW) at 2,700&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|2,500|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW) at 2,500&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|25,000|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; 2,300&nbsp;hp (1,700&nbsp;kW) WEP with water injection. Main production variant used in P-47 series, fed by an improved C-23 turbosupercharger.<ref>Bodie 1994, p. 392.</ref> Differed from -21 in being fitted with A.D.I and a General Electric ignition system with a simplified, tubular ignition harness developed by the Scinitilla company in partnership with Bendix. Used in P-47C and D, XP-47L. Production = 11,391 (P&W 592; Ford 10,799).<ref name=\"Wh280\">White 2001, p. 280.</ref> {{#tag:ref|'''R-2800-63''' with small manufacturing differences was interchangeable with -21 or -59 . Production =2,092 (P&W 1,262; Ford 767).<ref name=\"Wh280\"/>|group=nb}}\n* '''R-2800-59W''' - 2,500&nbsp;hp (1,890&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-65''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-65W''' - 2,250&nbsp;hp (1,677&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-71''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-75''' - 2,200&nbsp;hp (1,640&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-79''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n\n''\"C\" Series''\n[[File:HARP Pratt & Whitney R-2800 Double Wasp.JPG|thumb|A \"C Series\" R-2800, with the two section nose casing incorporating torque-monitoring equipment and a Spark Advance unit, with the \"outboard\" sparkplug wiring conduit location for each of the twin enclosed distributors.]]\n\n* '''R-2800-18W'''\n:2,100&nbsp;hp (1,566&nbsp;kW) at 2,800&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|1,000|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}; 1,800&nbsp;hp (1,342&nbsp;kW) at 2,800&nbsp;rpm at {{convert|25,500|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>USN history 1986, p. 8.</ref> First series production variant of the \"C\" Series, which was a complete redesign of the R-2800. Some of the main changes were [[Forge#Drop forging|forged]], rather than [[Continuous casting|cast]] cylinders, allowing an increased compression ratio (from 6.65:1 to 6.75:1), a redesigned crankshaft, a single piece, rather than split crankcase center section, and a two section nose casing, incorporating hydraulically operated [[Dynamometer#Hydraulic brake|torque-monitoring]] equipment and an automatic, vacuum operated [[Ignition timing#Vacuum timing advance|spark-advance]] unit.<ref>White 2001, pp. 163-165, 167-169.</ref> The supercharger used [[fluid coupling]] for the second stage.<ref>White 2001, pp. 144-145, 148-152, 158-160.</ref> Updraft Bendix-Stromberg PT-13G2-10 carburetor. Used in [[Vought F4U Corsair#F4U-4|Vought F4U-4 and -4 variants]].{{#tag:ref|Because the \"C\" series engines ran more smoothly than previous R-2800s the F4U-4 was able to use simplified, solid engine mountings rather than needing mountings incorporating shock absorbers.<ref>White 2001, pp. 432, 437.</ref>|group=nb}} Production = 3,257 (P&W).<ref>White 2001, p. 257.</ref>\n\n* '''R-2800-22W''' - 2,400&nbsp;hp (1,789&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-34''' - 2,100&nbsp;hp (1,567&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-34W''' - 2,100&nbsp;hp<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.ww2aircraft.net/forum/engines/terminology-engine-data-36560-3.html#post1006503 |title = Terminology and engine data}}</ref> (1,567&nbsp;kW), 2,400&nbsp;hp (1,789&nbsp;kW) with water-methanol injection\n* '''R-2800-44''' - 2,300&nbsp;hp (1,700&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-44W''' - 2,400&nbsp;hp (1,789&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-48''' - 2,500&nbsp;hp (1,890&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-48W''' - 2,400&nbsp;hp (1,789&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-54''' - 2,100&nbsp;hp (1,567&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-57''' - 2,800&nbsp;hp (2,090&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-57C''' - 2,800&nbsp;hp (2,090&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-73''' - 2,800&nbsp;hp (2,090&nbsp;kW) \u2014 with General Electric CH-5-A3 turbocharger<ref>[https://aviationshoppe.com/manuals/wwii_aircraft_superchargers/wwii_aircraft_turbosupercharger.html GE Turbocharger Manual \"Section XIX\" for its CH-5 series turbochargers, pgs. 206-209]</ref> for P-61C Black Widow\n* '''R-2800-77''' - 2,800&nbsp;hp (2,090&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-83''' - 2,100&nbsp;hp (1,567&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-83AM''' - 2,100&nbsp;hp (1,567&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-99W''' - 2,300&nbsp;hp (1,700&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-103W''' - 2,500&nbsp;hp (1,890&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-2SB-G''' - 1,850&nbsp;hp (1,379&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-CB16''' - 2,400&nbsp;hp (1,789&nbsp;kW), 2,500&nbsp;hp (1,890&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-CB17''' - 2,500&nbsp;hp (1,890&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-S1A4-G''' - 1,850&nbsp;hp (1,379&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-S1C3-G''' - 2,100&nbsp;hp (1,567&nbsp;kW)\n\n''\"D\" Series:''\n* '''R-2800-23''' - 2,200&nbsp;hp (1,640&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-29''' - 2,000&nbsp;hp (1,491&nbsp;kW)\n\n''\"E\" Series:''\n* '''R-2800-30W ''' - 2,250&nbsp;hp (1,677&nbsp;kW)\n* '''R-2800-32W ''' - 2,450&nbsp;hp (1,827&nbsp;kW), 2,850&nbsp;hp (2,125&nbsp;kW) with water-methanol injection\n\n==Applications==\n[[File:B26-dinah-might-899.jpg|Martin B-26 Marauder|thumb|right]]\nThe following is a partial list of aircraft that were powered by the R-2800 (and a few prototypes that utilized it at one point):\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Brewster XA-32]]\n* [[Breguet Deux-Ponts]]\n* [[Canadair CL-215]]\n* [[Canadair North Star|Canadair C-5 North Star]]\n* [[Consolidated TBY Sea Wolf]]\n* [[Convair CV-240 family|Convair 240, 340, and 440]]\n* [[Curtiss P-60]]\n* [[Curtiss XF15C]]\n* [[Curtiss C-46 Commando]]\n* [[Douglas A-26 Invader]]\n* [[Douglas DC-6]]\n* [[Fairchild C-82 Packet]]\n* [[Fairchild C-123 Provider]]\n* [[Grumman AF Guardian]]\n* [[Grumman F6F Hellcat]]\n* [[Grumman F7F Tigercat]]\n* [[Grumman F8F Bearcat]]\n* [[Howard 500]]\n* [[Lockheed Ventura|Lockheed Ventura/B-34 Lexington/PV-1 Ventura/PV-2 Harpoon]]\n* [[Lockheed C-69 Constellation|Lockheed XC-69E Constellation]]\n* [[Martin B-26 Marauder]]\n* [[Martin PBM-5 Mariner]]\n* [[Martin 2-0-2]]\n* [[Martin 4-0-4]]\n* [[North American AJ Savage]]\n* [[North American XB-28]]\n* [[Northrop XP-56 Black Bullet]]\n* [[Northrop P-61 Black Widow]]\n* [[Northrop F-15 Reporter]]\n* [[Republic P-47 Thunderbolt]]\n* [[Sikorsky CH-37 Mojave]]\n* [[Sikorsky S-60]]\n* [[Vickers Warwick]]\n* [[Vought F4U Corsair]]\n* [[Vultee A-19|Vultee YA-19B]]\n}}\n\n==Engines on display==\n* There is an R-2800-39 on display at the [[New England Air Museum]], [[Bradley International Airport]], Windsor Locks, CT.<ref>http://neam.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&layout=edit&id=1093 \"Pratt & Whitney R-2800-39 Double Wasp\"</ref>\n* An R-2800 used on [[Finnair]] [[Convair Metropolitan]] is on public display at [[Helsinki Airport]].{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n* An R-2800 Double Wasp is on display at the Aerospace Discovery at the [[Florida Air Museum]].{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n* An R-2800 Double Wasp manufactured by Ford Motor Company is on display at the [[Yankee Air Museum]] [[Belleville, Michigan]]<ref>Yankee Air Museum archives and floor display</ref>\n* An R-2800-8W Double Wasp is on display at the [[Flying Leatherneck Aviation Museum]] at [[MCAS Miramar]], [[California]].\n* An R-2800 Double Wasp moving cut-away is on display at the [[USS Midway Museum]] at [[San Diego]], [[California]].\n* An R-2800 Double Wasp is on display at (The National Museum of WWII Aviation) located in (Colorado Springs, Colorado).\n* An R-2800-34 Double Wasp is on public at the [[Aerospace Museum of California]].\n\n==Specifications (R-2800-54)==\n[[File:Pratt-Whitney R-2800.jpg|thumb|right|{{nowrap|Pratt & Whitney R-2800}}]]\n{{pistonspecs\n|<!-- If you do not understand how to use this template, please ask at [[Wikipedia talk:WikiProject Aircraft]] -->\n<!-- Please include units where appropriate (main comes first, alt in parentheses). If data are missing, leave the parameter blank (do not delete it). For additional lines, end your alt units with </li> and start a new, fully-formatted line with <li> -->\n|type=18-cylinder air-cooled twin-row [[radial engine]] with water injection\n|ref=FAA TCDS<ref>[http://www.airweb.faa.gov/Regulatory_and_Guidance_Library%5CrgMakeModel.nsf/0/CF0F9435E20432008525676A006759E7/$FILE/5E-8.pdf FAA Type Certificate Data Sheet] Retrieved: 30 October 2008</ref>\n|bore=5.75 in (146.05 mm)\n|stroke=6 in (152.4 mm)\n|displacement=2,804.5 in\u00b3 (45.96 L) \n|length=81.4 in (2,068 mm)\n|diameter=52.8 in (1,342 mm)\n|width=\n|height=\n|weight=2,360 lb (1,073 kg)\n|valvetrain=[[Poppet valve|Poppet]], two valves per cylinder\n|supercharger=Variable-speed (in F8F-2, unified with throttle via AEC automatic engine control), single-stage single-speed [[centrifugal type supercharger]]\n|turbocharger=\n|fuelsystem=One [[Stromberg (Carburetor brandname)|Stromberg]] [[Pressure carburetor|injection carburetor]]\n|fueltype=100/130 [[Octane rating|octane]] gasoline\n|oilsystem=\n|coolingsystem=Air-cooled\n|power=2,100 hp (1,567 kW) @ 2,700 rpm \n|specpower=0.75 hp/in\u00b3 (34.1 kW/L)\n|compression=\n|fuelcon=\n|specfuelcon=\n|oilcon=\n|power/weight=0.89 hp/lb (1.46 kW/kg)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Aircontent\n|related=\n* [[Pratt & Whitney Wasp]] series\n* [[Pratt & Whitney R-985 Wasp Junior]] \n* [[Pratt & Whitney R-1340 Wasp]] \n* [[Pratt & Whitney R-1535 Twin Wasp Junior]] \n* [[Pratt & Whitney R-1830 Twin Wasp]] \n* [[Pratt & Whitney R-2000 Twin Wasp]] \n* [[Pratt & Whitney R-4360 Wasp Major]]\n|similar engines=\n* [[Alfa Romeo 135]]\n* [[BMW 802]]\n* [[Bristol Centaurus]]\n* [[Fiat A.80]]\n* [[Fiat A.82]]\n* [[Gnome-Rh\u00f4ne 18L]]\n* [[Nakajima Homare]]\n* [[Shvetsov ASh-73]]\n* [[Wright R-3350]]\n\n|lists=\n* [[List of aircraft engines]]\n|see also=\n}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Bodie, Warren M. ''Republic's P-47 Thunderbolt: From Seversky to Victory''. Hayesville, North Carolina: Widewing Publications, 1994. {{ISBN|0-9629359-1-3}}\n*Gunston, Bill. ''World Encyclopedia of Aero Engines: From the Pioneers to the Present Day''. 5th edition, Stroud, UK: Sutton, 2006.{{ISBN|0-7509-4479-X}}\n*{{Ref Jane's|||1951}}\n*White, Graham. ''Allied Aircraft Piston Engines of World War II: History and Development of Frontline Aircraft Piston Engines Produced by Great Britain and the United States During World War II''. Warrendale, Pennsylvania: SAE International, 1995. {{ISBN|1-56091-655-9}}\n*White, Graham. ''R-2800: Pratt & Whitney's Dependable Masterpiece''. Shrewsbury, UK: Airlife Publishing, 2001. {{ISBN|1-84037-335-0}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pratt & Whitney R-2800}}\n* [http://www.pw.utc.com/R2800_Double_Wasp_Engine Pratt & Whitney's R-2800 page]\n* [http://www.aviation-history.com/engines/pr-2800.htm The Aviation History Online Museum's Double Wasp page]\n\n{{P&W piston engines}}\n{{US military piston aeroengines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pratt and Whitney R-2800 Double Wasp}}\n[[Category:Radial engines]]\n[[Category:Pratt & Whitney aircraft engines|R-2800]]\n[[Category:1930s aircraft piston engines]]\n", "name_user": "TABowland", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grumman F8F Bearcat added to major applications", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pratt_%26_Whitney_R-2800_Double_Wasp"}
{"title_page": "What Is Life", "text_new": "{{About|the George Harrison song|other uses|What Is Life (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = What Is Life\n| cover      = What Is Life (George Harrison single - cover art).jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| caption    = US picture sleeve\n| type       = single777824\n| artist     = [[George Harrison]]\n| album      = [[All Things Must Pass]]\n| A-side     = \"[[My Sweet Lord]]\" <small>(UK)</small>\n| B-side     = \"[[Apple Scruffs (song)|Apple Scruffs]]\" <small>(except UK)</small>\n| released   = 15 February 1971 (US)\n| format     = [[gramophone record|7-inch vinyl]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Soul music|soul]]\n| length     = 4:22\n| label      = [[Aple Records|Apple]]\n| writer     = [[George Harrison]]\n| producer   = George Harrison, [[Phil Spector]]\n| prev_title = [[My Sweet Lord]]\n| prev_year  = 1970\n| next_title = [[Bangla Desh (song)|Bangla Desh]]\n| next_year  = 1971\n| misc       = {{xtra track listing\n | album  = [[All Things Must Pass]]\n | type   = single777824\n | tracks = {{All Things Must Pass tracks}}\n}}\n}}\n\"'''What Is Life'''\" is a song by the English musician [[George Harrison]], released on his 1970 triple album ''[[All Things Must Pass]]''. In many countries, it was issued as the second [[single (music)|single]] from the album, in February 1971, becoming a top-ten hit in the United States, Canada and elsewhere, and topping singles charts in Australia and Switzerland. In the United Kingdom, \"What Is Life\" appeared as the [[B-side]] to \"[[My Sweet Lord]]\", which was the best-selling single there of 1971. Harrison's backing musicians on the song include [[Eric Clapton]] and the entire [[Delaney & Bonnie|Delaney & Bonnie and Friends]] band, with whom he had toured during the final months of [[the Beatles]]. Harrison co-produced the recording with [[Phil Spector]], whose [[Wall of Sound]] production also employed a prominent string arrangement by [[John Barham]] and multiple acoustic rhythm guitars, played by Harrison's fellow [[Apple Records]] signings [[Badfinger]].\n\nAn uptempo composition in the [[Soul music|soul]] genre, \"What Is Life\" is one of several Harrison love songs that appear to be directed at both a woman and a deity. Harrison wrote the song in 1969 and originally intended it as a track for his friend and Apple prot\u00e9g\u00e9 [[Billy Preston]] to record. Built around a descending [[guitar riff]], it is one of Harrison's most popular compositions and was a regular inclusion in his live performances. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine has variously described it as a \"classic\"<ref name=\"RS 500 Albums\" /> and an \"exultant song of surrender\".<ref name=\"Eds of RS p 201\" />\n\n\"What Is Life\" has appeared in the soundtrack for feature films such as ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990), ''[[Patch Adams (film)|Patch Adams]]'' (1998), ''[[Big Daddy (1999 film)|Big Daddy]]'' (1999), ''[[Away We Go (film)|Away We Go]]'' (2009), ''[[This Is 40]]'' (2012) and ''[[Instant Family]]'' (2018). Harrison's original recording was included on the compilations ''[[The Best of George Harrison]]'' and ''[[Let It Roll: Songs by George Harrison|Let It Roll]]'', and live versions appear on his album ''[[Live in Japan (George Harrison album)|Live in Japan]]'' (1992) and in [[Martin Scorsese]]'s 2011 documentary ''[[George Harrison: Living in the Material World]]''. In 1972, [[Olivia Newton-John]] had a UK hit with her version of the song. [[Ronnie Aldrich]], [[the Ventures]] and [[Shawn Mullins]] are among the other artists who have covered the track.\n\n==Background and composition==\nEven before his temporary departure from [[the Beatles]] in January 1969 (documented in the song \"[[Wah-Wah (song)|Wah-Wah]]\"),<ref>Rodriguez, p. 379.</ref> their [[Apple Records]] label was an \"emancipating force\" for Harrison from the creative restrictions imposed on him within the band, according to his musical biographer, Simon Leng.<ref>Leng, pp. 55, 85.</ref> In his \"definitive\" article on ''[[All Things Must Pass]]'' for ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' magazine, [[John Harris (critic)|John Harris]] has written of Harrison's \"journey\" as a solo artist beginning in November 1968 \u2013 when he spent time in [[Woodstock, New York|Woodstock]] with [[Bob Dylan]] and [[the Band]] \u2013 and incorporating a series of other collaborations through the following eighteen months, including various Apple projects and a support role on [[Delaney & Bonnie]] and Friends' brief European tour.<ref>Harris, pp. 68\u201373.</ref> One of these projects, carried out intermittently from April to July 1969,<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, p. 80.</ref> was his production of ''[[That's the Way God Planned It]]'', an album by [[Billy Preston]], whom Harrison had met during the Beatles' [[The Beatles in Hamburg|Hamburg years]] and had recently recruited to guest on the band's troubled [[Let It Be (Beatles album)|''Get Back'']] sessions.<ref name=\"Irvin/Mojo p 82\">Jim Irvin, \"Close to the Edge\", ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'', December 2003, p. 82.</ref><ref>[http://applerecords.com/#!/albums/Album_EncouragingWords \"Encouraging Words\"], [[Apple Records]] (retrieved 16 February 2012).</ref> It was while driving up to a Preston session in London from his [[Kinfauns (Surrey)|home]] in [[Esher|Esher, Surrey]], that Harrison came up with the song \"What Is Life\".<ref name=\"Spizer p 222\">Spizer, p. 222.</ref>\n\nIn his autobiography, ''[[I, Me, Mine (book)|I, Me, Mine]]'', Harrison describes it as having been written \"very quickly\" and recalls that he thought it would be a perfect, \"catchy pop song\" for Preston to record.<ref name=\"IMM p 162\">George Harrison, p. 162.</ref> His lyrics, while simple, were similarly uplifting and universal:<ref name=\"Inglis p 26\">Inglis, p. 26.</ref><ref name=\"Unterberger/AM\" />\n\n{{quote|''What I feel, I can't say <br> But my love is there for you any time of day <br> But if it's not love that you need <br> Then I'll try my best to make everything succeed. <br> <br>Tell me, what is my life without your love? <br> And tell me, who am I without you, by my side?''}}\n\nThese lyrics have caused some debate among biographers and music critics, as to whether \"What Is Life\" should be viewed as a straightforward love song \u2013 perhaps a \"lovingly crafted paen\" to Harrison's wife [[Pattie Boyd|Pattie]], as [[Alan Clayson]] puts it<ref>Clayson, p. 298.</ref> \u2013 or a [[devotional song]] like many of Harrison's compositions.<ref name=\"Unterberger/AM\" /><ref>Allison, p. 158.</ref> Ian Inglis writes that the song title suggests a \"philosophical debate about the meaning of life\", yet its rendering as \"''what is my life''\" in the choruses \"reshapes [the meaning] completely\".<ref name=\"Inglis p 26\" /> Theologian [[Dale Allison]] finds no religious content in \"What Is Life\" but notes the \"failure of words to express feelings\" implied in the opening line (\"''What I feel, I can't say''\"), a recurring theme of Harrison's [[Spirituality|spiritual]] songs such as \"[[That Is All (song)|That Is All]]\", \"[[Mystical One]]\" and \"[[Pisces Fish]]\".<ref>Allison, pp. 124, 158.</ref> Joshua Greene, another religious academic, identifies the song as part of its parent album's \"intimately detailed account of a spiritual journey\": where \"[[Awaiting on You All]]\" shows Harrison \"convinced of his union with God\", \"What Is Life\" reveals him to be \"uncertain that he deserved such divine favor\".<ref>Greene, p. 181.</ref>\n\nThe song's second verse repeats what Inglis refers to as the \"somewhat confusing promise\" from Harrison (in lines 3 and 4) should his love be \"rejected\":<ref name=\"Inglis p 26\" />\n\n{{quote|''What I know, I can do <br> If I give my love out to everyone like you <br> But if it's not love that you need <br> Then I'll try my best to make everything succeed.''}}\n\nMusically, Simon Leng describes \"What Is Life\" as \"[[Motown]]-spiced\" and a comparatively rare example of its composer's willingness to embrace the role of \"entertainer\" in his songwriting.<ref>Leng, pp. 87\u201388.</ref>\n\nIn ''I Me Mine'', Harrison recalls that he changed his mind about offering \"What Is Life\" to Preston once he'd arrived at [[Olympic Studios]] and found the singer busy working on more typical material \u2013 or \"playing his funky stuff\" as Harrison puts it.<ref name=\"IMM p 162\" /><ref name=\"Spizer p 222\" /> Rather than attempt it with the Beatles during the band's concurrent ''[[Abbey Road]]'' sessions, he stockpiled the track with his many other unused songs from the period \u2013 \"[[All Things Must Pass (song)|All Things Must Pass]]\", \"[[Let It Down]]\", \"[[I'd Have You Anytime]]\" and \"[[Run of the Mill (George Harrison song)|Run of the Mill]]\" among them<ref>The Editors of ''Rolling Stone'', p. 187.</ref> \u2013 and revisited it a year later, after completing work on Preston's second Apple album, ''[[Encouraging Words]]''.<ref>Madinger & Easter, p. 426.</ref>\n\n==Recording==\nBy May 1970, having recently collaborated with \"genuine [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] heavy-weights\" such as [[Doris Troy]] and Preston, as well as participating in the \"[[blue-eyed soul]]\"<ref>Clayson, p. 274.</ref> Delaney & Bonnie European tour, along with [[Eric Clapton]], the previous December, Harrison was well placed to record \"What Is Life\", Leng observes.<ref name=\"Leng p 88\">Leng, p. 88.</ref> With [[Phil Spector]] as co-producer and all the Friends team on hand, the song was among the first tracks taped for Harrison's debut post-Beatles solo album;<ref name=\"Madinger & Easter p 429\" /> recording took place at [[Abbey Road Studios]] in London, during late May or early June.<ref name=\"Madinger & Easter p 429\" /><ref>Badman, p. 10.</ref> The same core of musicians \u2013 [[Bobby Whitlock]], [[Carl Radle]], [[Jim Gordon (musician)|Jim Gordon]], [[Bobby Keys]] and [[Jim Price (musician)|Jim Price]] \u2013 would similarly elevate other ''All Things Must Pass'' tracks such as \"Awaiting on You All\", \"[[Art of Dying (song)|Art of Dying]]\" and \"[[Hear Me Lord]]\".<ref>Leng, pp. 95\u201396, 97\u201398, 99.</ref>\n\nThe recording is defined by Harrison's descending, [[distortion (music)|fuzztone]] guitar [[riff]],<ref name=\"Eds of RS p 201\" /> which also serves as the [[motif (music)|motif]] for the chorus.<ref name=\"Unterberger/AM\">Richie Unterberger, [http://www.allmusic.com/song/what-is-life-t743156 \"George Harrison 'What Is Life'\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 22 February 2012).</ref> The track opens with this riff,<ref name=\"Gallucci/UCR\" /> which is then joined by Radle's bass and \"churning\" rhythm guitar from Clapton, before Gordon's drums bring the full band in.<ref name=\"Spizer p 222\" /><ref name=\"Leng p 87\" /> During the verses, Gordon moves to a square, Motown-style beat \u2013 or \"rock-steady [[Northern soul]] [[Beat (music)#Backbeat|backbeat]]\" in Leng's words<ref name=\"Leng p 88\" /> \u2013 before returning to the \"galloping rhythm\" of the more open, \"knockout\" choruses,<ref name=\"Eds of RS p 201\" /> and the song is driven equally by [[Badfinger]] drummer [[Mike Gibbins]]' powerful tambourine work.<ref name=\"Clayson p 296\" />\n\nOn \"What Is Life\", Spector provided what music critic [[David Fricke]] terms \"echo-drenched theater\", in the form of [[reverberation|reverb]]-heavy brass, soaring strings (arranged by [[John Barham]]) and \"a choir of multitracked Harrisons\".<ref name=\"Eds of RS p 201\">The Editors of ''Rolling Stone'', p. 201.</ref> The vocals and Barham's contribution, along with a brief [[Slide guitar|slide-guitar]] commentary from Harrison over the final verse,<ref name=\"Unterberger/AM\" /> were [[Overdubbing|overdubbed]] at [[Trident Studios]], most likely during late August through September.<ref>Madinger & Easter, pp. 427, 429.</ref> Dated 19 August, Spector's written comments on Harrison's early mix of the song had suggested a \"proper background voice\" was still needed;<ref name=\"Beatles Bible album\">[http://www.beatlesbible.com/people/george-harrison/albums/all-things-must-pass/ George Harrison: All Things Must Pass (album)], The Beatles Bible (retrieved 20 October 2012).</ref> like sound engineer [[Ken Scott]],<ref name=\"Beatles Bible\">[http://www.beatlesbible.com/people/george-harrison/songs/what-is-life/ George Harrison: What Is Life], The Beatles Bible (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref> Spector would be impressed with the result, saying, \"He was a great harmoniser&nbsp;... he could do all the [vocal] parts himself\" and rating Harrison \"one of the most commercial musicians and songwriters and quintessential players I've ever known in my entire career\".<ref>Olivia Harrison, p. 282.</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\"What Is Life\" was released in late November 1970 as the first track on side two of ''All Things Must Pass'', in its original, triple [[LP record|LP]] format.<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, p. 94.</ref><ref name=\"Spizer p 220\">Spizer, p. 220.</ref> Along with \"[[My Sweet Lord]]\" and \"[[Isn't It a Pity]]\", the song had already been identified as a potential hit single by Allan Steckler, manager of Apple's US operation.<ref name=\"Spizer p 220\" /> Backed by another album track, \"[[Apple Scruffs (song)|Apple Scruffs]]\", \"What Is Life\" was issued as a single in America on 15 February 1971 (as Apple 1828), just as the \"My Sweet Lord\"/\"Isn't It a Pity\" [[A-side and B-side#Double A-side|double A-side]] was finally slipping out of the top ten.<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, pp. 99, 352.</ref><ref>Badman, p. 26.</ref>\n\n[[File:Wil france.jpg|thumb|right|160px|French picture sleeve for the \"What Is Life\" single \u2013 a cropped and colorized version of [[Barry Feinstein]]'s cover image for ''[[All Things Must Pass]]'']]\nThe front of the single's US [[Record sleeve|picture sleeve]] consisted of a photo of Harrison playing guitar inside the central tower of his recently purchased home, [[Friar Park]], in [[Henley-on-Thames]].<ref>Spizer, pp. 226, 231.</ref> The tower's sole, octagonal-shaped room was an area that Harrison had adopted as his personal temple and [[meditation]] space.<ref>Tillery, p. 90.</ref> This picture was taken by photographer [[Barry Feinstein]], whose Camouflage Productions partner, [[Tom Wilkes]], originally used it as part of an elaborate poster intended as an insert in the album package. The poster featured a painting of the [[Hinduism|Hindu]] deity [[Krishna]] watching a group of naked maidens beside a bathing pond.<ref name=\"Spizer p 226\">Spizer, p. 226.</ref> Harrison apparently felt uncomfortable with the symbolism in Wilkes's design \u2013 the Friar Park tower image filled the top half of the poster, floating among clouds above the Krishna scene \u2013 so Wilkes abandoned the concept and instead used a darkened photo of Harrison inside the house as the album poster.<ref>Spizer, pp. 221, 226\u201328.</ref> The more common picture sleeve internationally was a close-up of Feinstein's ''All Things Must Pass'' front-cover image, taken on the main lawn of Friar Park.<ref>Harris, p. 73.</ref> In Denmark, the sleeve featured four shots of Harrison, again with guitar,<ref>Schaffner, p. 142.</ref> taken on stage during the Delaney & Bonnie tour.<ref>Peter Doggett, \"The Apple Years\", ''[[Record Collector]]'', April 2001, p. 36.</ref>\n\nAt the end of March, \"What Is Life\" peaked at number 10 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, p. 352.</ref> and number 7 on ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]''{{'}}s Top 100 chart,<ref name=\"Spizer p 231\">Spizer, p. 231.</ref> making Harrison the first ex-Beatle to have two top-ten hits in the United States.<ref>Rodriguez, p. 48.</ref><ref name=\"Mapes/Billboard\">Jillian Mapes, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/464932/george-harrisons-10-biggest-billboard-hits \"George Harrison's 10 Biggest Billboard Hits\"], [[Billboard (magazine)|billboard.com]], 29 November 2011 (retrieved 4 June 2014).</ref> The single was a success internationally, climbing to number 1 in Switzerland<ref name=\"chchart\" /> and on Australia's ''[[Go-Set]]'' National Top 60,<ref name=\"auschart\" /> and reaching the top three elsewhere in Europe and in Canada.<ref name=\"Tsosrt/GH singles\">[http://tsort.info/music/azncfw.htm \"George Harrison (Song artist 225)\"], Tsort pages (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref> In Britain, where Harrison had resisted issuing a single from ''All Things Must Pass'' until midway through January,<ref>Badman, pp. 22, 59.</ref> \"What Is Life\" appeared on the B-side to \"My Sweet Lord\"<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, p. 99.</ref> \u2013 a combination that became the [[List of best-selling singles by year in the United Kingdom|top-selling single]] of 1971 in that country.<ref>Dan Lane, [http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-biggest-selling-singles-of-every-year-revealed-1952-2011-1720/ \"The biggest selling singles of every year revealed! (1952\u20132011)\"], [[Official Charts Company]], 18 November 2012 (retrieved 3 June 2014).</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\"What Is Life\" is one of Harrison's most commercial and popular songs<ref>Allison, p. 132.</ref> \u2013 a \"spiritual guitar quest\" that \"became [a] classic\", according to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"RS 500 Albums\">[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/george-harrison-all-things-must-pass-19691231 \"500 Greatest Albums of All Time: George Harrison, 'All Things Must Pass'\"], [[Rolling Stone|rollingstone.com]] (retrieved 5 June 2014).</ref> On release, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine's reviewer wrote of \"What Is Life\" and \"Apple Scruffs\" as \"intriguing rhythm follows-ups\" to Harrison's previous single, which were \"sure to repeat that success\" and \"should prove big juke box items\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?hl=pt-BR&id=6QgEAAAAMBAJ&q=what+is+life#v=snippet&q=%22What%20is%20life%22&f=false \"Spotlight Singles\"], ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', 20 February 1971, p. 62 (retrieved 13 October 2013).</ref> In their ''Solo Beatles Compendium'', authors Chip Madinger and Mark Easter refer to it as an \"intensely catchy track\" and view its pairing with \"My Sweet Lord\" in the UK as perhaps the strongest of all of Harrison's singles.<ref name=\"Madinger & Easter p 429\">Madinger & Easter, p. 429.</ref> Writing in 1981, ''[[NME]]'' critic [[Bob Woffinden]] grouped \"What Is LIfe\" with \"My Sweet Lord\", \"Isn't It a Pity\" and \"Awaiting on You All\" as \"all excellent songs\".<ref>Woffinden, p. 38.</ref>\n\nReviewing the [[All Things Must Pass#2001|2001 reissue]] of ''All Things Must Pass'', for ''Rolling Stone'', James Hunter wrote of how the album's music \"exults in breezy rhythms\", among which \"the colorful revolutions of 'What Is Life' ... [move] like a [[Ferris wheel]]\".<ref>James Hunter, \"George Harrison ''All Things Must Pass'' 30th Anniversary reissue\", ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 29 March 2001; quoted in The Super Seventies \"Classic 500\", [http://www.superseventies.com/harrison1.html George Harrison \u2013 ''All Things Must Pass''] (retrieved 19 October 2012).</ref> The following year, in Rolling Stone Press's ''Harrison'' tribute book, David Fricke included \"What Is Life\" among his selection of \"essential Harrison performances\" (just three of which date from the ex-Beatle's solo years) and described the track as an \"exultant song of surrender\", abetted by Harrison's \"pumping [[Distortion (music)|fuzz guitar]]\" and the song's \"singalong magnetism\".<ref>The Editors of ''Rolling Stone'', pp. 196\u2013201.</ref> [[AllMusic]]'s [[Richie Unterberger]] similarly praises \"What Is Life\" for its \"anthemic\" qualities, \"particularly snazzy horn lines\", and a guitar riff that is \"one more entry in the catalog of George Harrison's book of arresting, low, descending guitar lines\".<ref name=\"Unterberger/AM\" />\n\nWriting in the book ''[[1,000 Recordings to Hear Before You Die]]'', author [[Tom Moon]] refers to \"the upbeat single 'What Is Life'\" as an example of how Harrison \"grabs what he needs from his old band \u2013 that insinuating [[Hook (music)|hook]] sense \u2013 and uses it to frame an utterly comfortable metaphysical discourse\".<ref name=\"Moon\">Moon, p. 345.</ref> Alan Clayson describes \"What Is Life\" as a seemingly \"lovey-dovey pop song\" that \"craftily renewed the simplistic tonic-to-dominant riff clich\u00e9\",<ref name=\"Clayson p 296\">Clayson, p. 296.</ref> while Simon Leng credits Harrison's \"innate ability to write very fine pop-rock songs\" and deems the result \"as innovative an exercise in rock-soul as The Temptations' '[[Cloud Nine (The Temptations song)|Cloud Nine]]'\".<ref name=\"Leng p 88\" /> Among Harrison biographers, only Ian Inglis is less than enthusiastic, acknowledging that Barham's orchestration and the other musicians give the track \"undoubted excitement and energy\", but lamenting that the song offers \"little overall coherence between words and music\".<ref name=\"Inglis p 26\" />\n\nIn a 2010 poll to find the \"10 Best George Harrison Songs\", [[AOL Radio]] listeners voted \"What Is Life\" third behind \"My Sweet Lord\" and \"[[Blow Away]]\".<ref>Boonsri Dickinson, [http://www.aolradioblog.com/2010/04/03/best-george-harrison-songs/ \"10 Best George Harrison Songs\"], [[AOL Radio]], April 2010 (retrieved 27 July 2012).</ref> A similar list by Michael Galluci of [[Ultimate Classic Rock]] placed it second (behind \"My Sweet Lord\"), as Galluci wrote of the track having \"a giant pop hook as its guide\" as well as \"the catchiest chorus Harrison ever penned\".<ref name=\"Gallucci/UCR\">Michael Gallucci, [http://ultimateclassicrock.com/george-harrison-songs/ \"Top 10 George Harrison Songs\"], [[Ultimate Classic Rock]] (retrieved 28 March 2014).</ref> In 2009, Matt Melis of [[Consequence of Sound]] listed it sixth among his \"Top Ten Songs by Ex-Beatles\", writing: \"it's arguable that Harrison's ''All Things Must Pass'' is the best solo album put out by a Beatle. 'What is Life' \u2026 with its riff-driven bounce, soaring harmonies on the choruses, and perfectly placed sax and trumpet, [is] probably Harrison's catchiest pop song.\"<ref>Matt Melis, [http://consequenceofsound.net/2009/04/list-em-carefully-top-ten-songs-by-ex-beatles/ \"List 'Em Carefully: Top Ten Songs by Ex-Beatles\"], [[Consequence of Sound]], 8 April 2009 (retrieved 28 March 2014).</ref> In the 2005 publication ''[[NME Originals]]: Beatles \u2013 The Solo Years 1970\u20131980'', Adrian Thrills rated it first among Harrison's \"ten solo gems\", adding: \"One of Harrison's greatest guitar riffs \u2013 brilliant pop.\"<ref>Chris Hunt (ed.), ''[[NME|NME Originals]]: Beatles \u2013 The Solo Years 1970\u20131980'', [[IPC Media \u2013 Inspire (Time Inc.)#Inspire|IPC Ignite!]] (London, 2005), p. 23.</ref> The song is said to be a favourite of [[Foo Fighters]] singer [[Dave Grohl]].<ref name=\"Eds of RS p 201\" /> In a ''Rolling Stone'' readers' poll, titled \"10 Greatest Solo Beatle Songs\", the song placed fourth, with the editor commenting: \"The track is deceptively simple, and more layers become apparent the more often you play it.\"<ref name=\"RS soloBeatles\">Andy Greene, [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/readers-poll-the-10-greatest-solo-beatle-songs-20130605/4-george-harrison-what-is-life-0593944 \"4. George Harrison \u2013 'What Is Life'\"], [[rollingstone.com]], 5 June 2013 (retrieved 30 May 2015).</ref> \"What Is Life\" has featured in Bruce Pollock's book ''The 7,500 Most Important Songs of 1944\u20132000'', Treble website's \"The Top 200 Songs of the 1970s\" (ranked at number 101) and [[Dave Thompson (author)|Dave Thompson]]'s ''1000 Songs That Rock Your World'' (at number 247).<ref>[http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/S6532.htm \"George Harrison 'What Is Life'\"], [[Acclaimed Music]] (retrieved 9 December 2014).</ref>\n\n==Subsequent releases and appearances in films==\n\"What Is Life\" was included on the 1976 compilation ''[[The Best of George Harrison]]'' as well as 2009's ''[[Let It Roll: Songs by George Harrison]]''.<ref>Inglis, pp. 65, 128.</ref> The song has also been featured in a number of popular movies: [[Martin Scorsese]]'s ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990), during the \"May 11, 1980\" sequence; [[Tom Shadyac]]'s ''[[Patch Adams (film)|Patch Adams]]'' (1998); [[Sam Mendes]]' ''[[Away We Go (film)|Away We Go]]'' (2009); and, more recently, ''[[Instant Family]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"imdb\">[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0365600/ \"George Harrison: Soundtrack\"], [[Internet Movie Database|IMDb]] (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref> In late 2012, \"What Is Life\" was used in advance promotion for the film ''[[This Is 40]]'', directed by [[Judd Apatow]],<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i9Vt9sP8OY8 \"''This Is 40'' Official Trailer #2 (2012)\"], YouTube, August 2012 (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref> although it was omitted from the accompanying soundtrack album.<ref>Stephen Thomas Erlewine, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-40-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0002441002 \"Various Artists ''This Is 40 (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 3 June 2014).</ref> According to ''Rolling Stone'': \"Today, many people know it merely as a song from all those soundtracks: it's in ''This Is 40'', ''Patch Adams'', ''Goodfellas'' and many more. It's almost as ubiquitous as '[[Let My Love Open the Door]]' or '[[Solsbury Hill (song)|Solsbury Hill]].'\"<ref name=\"RS soloBeatles\" /> In Scorsese's 2011 documentary ''[[George Harrison: Living in the Material World]]'', \"What Is Life\" plays over a sequence of 1969 photos of Harrison \u2013 with, variously, Preston, [[Jackie Lomax]], the [[Plastic Ono Band]], Clapton and [[Ravi Shankar]] \u2013 immediately before which, archive footage shows him discussing the restrictions he felt within the Beatles and how the band \"had to implode\".<ref>''George Harrison: Living in the Material World'', Disc 2; event occurs between 13:48 and 14:50.</ref>\n\nAn alternative studio version of \"What Is Life\" \u2013 in fact, a rough mix of the original backing track with different orchestration (in this case, [[piccolo trumpet]] and [[oboe]])<ref>Leng, p. 284.</ref> \u2013 was issued as one of five bonus tracks on the 2001 remaster of ''All Things Must Pass''.<ref>Huntley, p. 307.</ref> In the accompanying booklet, Harrison writes that this orchestral arrangement was discarded because he \"didn't like the feel\".<ref>George Harrison's liner notes, booklet accompanying ''All Things Must Pass'' reissue ([[Gnome Records]], 2001; produced by George Harrison & Phil Spector), p. 11.</ref> Speaking to ''Billboard'' editor-in-chief [[Timothy White (editor)|Timothy White]] in December 2000, Harrison explained the reason for the lack of a guide vocal on this version: \"I'm playing the fuzz guitar part that goes all through the song. So all I could do on the [initial] take was to give the band the cue line \u2013 the first line of each verse \u2013 and then go back to playing that riff. So that rough mix without the vocal \u2013 I'd forgot all about it \u2026\"<ref>Timothy White, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/80788/george-harrison-all-things-in-good-time \"George Harrison: 'All Things' In Good Time\"], [[Billboard (magazine)|billboard.com]], 8 January 2001 (retrieved 3 June 2014).</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, this instrumental version also appeared as a bonus track on the 2014 ''[[The Apple Years 1968\u201375|Apple Years 1968\u201375]]'' reissue of ''All Things Must Pass''.<ref name=\"Marchese/SecondDisc\">Joe Marchese, [http://theseconddisc.com/2014/09/02/give-me-love-george-harrisons-apple-years-are-collected-on-new-box-set/ \"Give Me Love: George Harrison\u2019s 'Apple Years' Are Collected On New Box Set\"], The Second Disc, 2 September 2014 (retrieved 26 September 2014).</ref>\n\n===Music video===\nCoinciding with the release of ''The Apple Years 1968\u201375'', Harrison's widow and son, [[Olivia Harrison|Olivia]] and [[Dhani Harrison]], held an online competition in which filmmakers were invited to create a video clip for \"What Is Life\". The winner would receive a $5000 cash prize and their entry would became the official video for the track, appearing on the Harrison [[YouTube]] channel and other media platforms.<ref>Steve Marinucci, [https://www.axs.com/olivia-dhani-harrison-to-choose-winner-of-what-is-life-music-video-con-19893 \"Olivia & Dhani Harrison to choose winner of 'What Is Life' music video contest\"], [[AXS (company)|axs.com]], 15 September 2014 (retrieved 21 May 2017).</ref> In November, Olivia and Dhani selected Brandon Moore of [[Oakland, CA]], as the winner, for his video featuring dance performances by Emma Rubinowitz and Esteban Hernandez of the [[San Francisco Ballet]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Genero.tv \u2018What is Life\u2019 Winner Announced |url=http://www.georgeharrison.com/genero-tv-what-is-life-winner-announced/ |website=georgeharrison.com |accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dancers in Yellow Frolic Around the Woods in the Official Video for the George Harrison\u2019s \u2018What Is Life\u2019 |url=https://laughingsquid.com/george-harrison-what-is-life/ |website=Laughing Squid |accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=George Harrison - What Is Life (Official Music Video) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fiH9edd25Bc |website=YouTube |publisher=George Harrison |accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Live performance==\nA live version of the song, recorded with Eric Clapton and his band in December 1991, is available on Harrison's 1992 album ''[[Live in Japan (George Harrison album)|Live in Japan]]'' album.<ref>Stephen Thomas Erlewine, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/live-in-japan-mw0000334804 \"George Harrison ''Live in Japan''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 20 October 2012).</ref> The performance was recorded at [[Tokyo Dome]] on 17 December,<ref>Madinger & Easter, pp. 483, 484.</ref> during the final show of the tour.<ref>Badman, pp. 471, 473.</ref>\n\nPart of a concert performance of \"What Is Life\" from Harrison's 1974 North American tour with Shankar is included in Scorsese's ''George Harrison: Living in the Material World''.<ref>''George Harrison: Living in the Material World'' Disc 2; event occurs between 50.51 and 51.49.</ref> While challenging the commonly held view that this controversial 1974 tour was a \"disaster\",<ref>Jim Miller, \"George Harrison: ''Dark Horse'' (LP Review)\", ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 13 February 1975, p. 180.</ref><ref>Rodriguez, p. 59.</ref> Simon Leng writes of a [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]] performance of \"What Is Life\" that was \"greeted with a reception that matched anything the New York audience at the [[The Concert for Bangladesh|Bangla Desh concerts]] expressed\".<ref>Leng, p. 172.</ref>\n\n==Cover versions==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = What Is Life\n| cover      = Picture sleeve for Olivia Newton-John single What Is Life.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Picture sleeve for the West German release (on [[Polydor Records]])\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Olivia Newton-John]]\n| album      = [[Olivia (Olivia Newton-John album)|Olivia]]\n| B-side     = I'm a Small and Lonely Light\n| released   = 1972\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]], [[Pop music|pop]]\n| length     = 3:21\n| label      = [[Pye International Records|Pye International]]\n| writer     = [[George Harrison]]\n| producer   = [[Bruce Welch]], [[John Farrar]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n===Olivia Newton-John===\nEnglish born Australian pop singer [[Olivia Newton-John]] recorded \"What Is Life\", along with a version of Harrison's ''All Things Must Pass'' track \"[[Behind That Locked Door]]\",<ref>[http://www.wer-singt.de/song_Behind+That+Locked+Door.htm \"Behind That Locked Door\"], wer-singt.de (retrieved 9 October 2012).</ref> for her 1972 album ''[[Olivia (Olivia Newton-John album)|Olivia]]''.<ref>[http://www.onlyolivia.com/music/albums/olivia.html \"Albums: ''Olivia''\"], onlyolivia.com (retrieved 9 October 2012).</ref> The song was arranged and produced by [[Bruce Welch]] of [[the Shadows]] and [[John Farrar]],<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=5710466 Label credit], \"What Is Life / I'm a Small and Lonely Light\" single, Interfusion Records, 1972.</ref> who was Newton-John's regular producer and collaborator during the 1970s.<ref>''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll'', pp. 709, 887.</ref>\n\nReleased as a single in some countries, this version reached the UK top 20 in March 1972,<ref name=\"Clayson p 296\" /><ref>Huntley, p. 56.</ref> peaking at number 16.<ref name=\"ONJ UK\" />{{refn|group=nb|Her previous single, a US hit in late 1971, was a cover of the Dylan song \"[[If Not For You]]\",<ref>''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll'', p. 709.</ref> based on the Harrison arrangement from ''All Things Must Pass'' rather than Dylan's own reading.<ref name=\"Clayson p 296\" /><ref>Joe Viglione, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/if-not-for-you-mw0000739358 \"Olivia Newton-John ''If Not for You''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 4 June 2014).</ref>}} It has since appeared on Newton-John compilation albums such as ''[[Back to Basics: The Essential Collection 1971\u20131992]]'' (1992)<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Olivia-Back-To-Basics-The-Essential-Collection-1971-1992/release/2974614 \"Olivia* \u2013 Back to Basics: The Essential Collection 1971\u20131992\"], [[Discogs]] (retrieved 14 June 2014).</ref> and ''[[The Definitive Collection (Olivia Newton-John album)|The Definitive Collection]]'' (2002).<ref>Heather Phares, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/definitive-collection-mw0000739711 \"Olivia Newton-John ''Definitive Collection''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 13 June 2014).</ref>\n\n===Other artists===\nIn 1971, British [[easy listening]] pianist [[Ronnie Aldrich]] covered \"What Is Life\" (as well as \"My Sweet Lord\") on his album ''Love Story''.<ref>Al Campbell, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/love-story-the-way-we-were-mw0000575419 \"Ronnie Aldridge ''Love Story / The Way We Were''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 16 September 2012).</ref> That same year, a version by [[the Ventures]] appeared on their ''New Testament'' album.<ref>Bruce Eder, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/new-testament-mw0000868440 \"The Ventures ''New Testament''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 4 August 2012).</ref> Also in 1971, a Finnish-language version of the song, titled \"Mik\u00e4 Saa Ihmisen El\u00e4m\u00e4\u00e4n\", was released as a single by local singer Oliver \u2013 better known as Veikko Laiho, of [[the Laiho Trio]].<ref>[http://finnpicks.blogspot.com.au/2011_03_01_archive.html \"What Is Life \u2013 Mik\u00e4 Saa Ihmisen El\u00e4m\u00e4\u00e4n\"], Finnpicks, 3 March 2011 (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref>\n\nIn 1992, [[Nicola Sirkis]] covered the song on the album ''Dans La Lune&nbsp;...''<ref name=\"GH covers\">[http://www.coversproject.com/artist/george%20harrison/ \"George Harrison Cover Songs\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221105921/https://www.coversproject.com/artist/george%20harrison |date=21 February 2017 }}, The Covers Project (retrieved 4 August 2012).</ref> A version by [[Shawn Mullins]] was released as a single in 1999<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Shawn-Mullins-What-Is-Life/release/3624755 \"Shawn Mullins \u2013 What Is Life\"], [[Discogs]] (retrieved 14 June 2014).</ref> and plays over the closing credits of the [[Adam Sandler]] movie ''[[Big Daddy (1999 film)|Big Daddy]]'' (1999).<ref name=\"imdb\" /><ref>Stephen Thomas Erlewine, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/big-daddy-mw0000241564 \"Original Soundtrack ''Big Daddy''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref>\n\nFollowing Harrison's death, Japanese band the Collectors contributed a recording of \"What Is Life\" to the ''Gentle Guitar Dreams'' tribute album, released in May 2002.<ref>[http://www.cdjapan.co.jp/detailview.html?KEY=AMCM-10021 \"Various Artists ''Gentle Guitar Dreams''\"], CD Japan (retrieved 15 September 2012).</ref> Classical guitarist Joseph Breznikar recorded a version of the song for his 2003 tribute album ''George Harrison Remembered: A Touch of Class''.<ref name=\"Breznikar\">[http://www.secondhandsongs.com/release/50957 \"''George Harrison Remembered: A Touch of Class'' \u2013 Joseph Breznikar\"], Second Hand Songs (retrieved 19 September 2012).</ref> In November 2004, [[Neal Morse]] released his recording of \"What Is Life\" on the special-edition version of his album ''[[One (Neal Morse album)|One]]''.<ref name=\"SecondHand various\">[http://www.secondhandsongs.com/work/72046 \"'What Is Life' \u2013 George Harrison\"], Second Hand Songs (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref> [[Les Fradkin]] included a cover of \"What Is Life\" on his 2005 tribute CD ''Something for George''.<ref>[http://www.lesfradkin.com/products-group-39.html \"George Harrison/Beatles Vocal Tribute CDs\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610001814/http://www.lesfradkin.com/products-group-39.html |date=10 June 2013 }}, lesfradkin.com (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref>\n\n\"What Is Life\" was performed live at George Fest 2014 by [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]]. The recording is available on YouTube.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wXMq3QJwJiA \"Weird Al Covers George Harrison's \"What is Life\" at George Fest 2014\"]</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nThe following musicians are believed to have played on \"What Is Life\":<ref name=\"Spizer p 222\"/><ref name=\"Leng p 87\">Leng, p. 87.</ref>\n\n* [[George Harrison]] \u2013 vocals, lead guitar, acoustic guitar, [[slide guitar]], backing vocals\n* [[Eric Clapton]] \u2013 rhythm guitar\n* [[Bobby Whitlock]] \u2013 organ<ref>Whitlock, p. 80.</ref>\n* [[Carl Radle]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Jim Gordon (musician)|Jim Gordon]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Jim Price (musician)|Jim Price]] \u2013 trumpet, horn arrangement\n* [[Bobby Keys]] \u2013 saxophone\n* [[Pete Ham]] \u2013 acoustic guitar\n* [[Tom Evans (musician)|Tom Evans]] \u2013 acoustic guitar\n* [[Joey Molland]] \u2013 acoustic guitar\n* [[Mike Gibbins]] \u2013 tambourine\n* [[John Barham]] \u2013 string arrangement\n\n==Chart performance==\n\n===George Harrison version===\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n;Weekly charts\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1971)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australian ''[[Go-Set]]'' National Top 60<ref name=\"auschart\">[http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1971/19710508.html \"Go-Set Australian charts \u2013 8 May 1971\"], poparchives.com.au (retrieved 13 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|[[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|Austrian Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"atchart\">[http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=George+Harrison&titel=What+Is+Life&cat=s \"George Harrison \u2013 What Is Life\"], austriancharts.at (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|Belgian [[Ultratop|Ultratop Singles]]<ref name=\"Belgian singles\">[http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=George+Harrison&titel=What+Is+Life&cat=s \"George Harrison \u2013 What Is Life\"], ultratop.be (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|Canadian [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'' 100 Singles]]<ref>[http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.5229&type=2&interval=24&PHPSESSID=tflvluuu3gmgse7n7epkm834m4 \"''RPM'' 100 Singles, 17 April 1971\"], [[Library and Archives Canada]] (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|Dutch [[MegaCharts|MegaChart Singles]]<ref name=\"nlchart\">[http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=George+Harrison&titel=What+Is+Life&cat=s \"George Harrison \u2013 What Is Life\"], dutchcharts.nl (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|Japanese [[Oricon]] Singles Chart<ref name=\"jpchart\">[http://homepage1.nifty.com/tuty/after_beatles_george_singlechartaction_japan.htm \"George Harrison: Chart Action (Japan)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303201239/http://homepage1.nifty.com/tuty/after_beatles_george_singlechartaction_japan.htm |date=3 March 2016 }}, homepage1.nifty.com (retrieved 11 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|19\n|-\n|New Zealand ''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'' Chart<ref name=\"NZchart\">[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20listener&qsongid=3899#n_view_location Search: \"What Is Life\"], Flavour of New Zealand/Steve Kohler, 2007 (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|Norwegian [[VG-lista|VG-lista Singles]]<ref name=\"nochart\">[http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=George+Harrison&titel=What+Is+Life&cat=s \"George Harrison \u2013 What Is Life\"], norwegiancharts.com (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|South African Springbok Singles Chart<ref>[http://www.rock.co.za/files/sa_charts_1969_1989_songs_(W-Z).html \"SA Charts 1969\u20131989 Songs (W\u2013Z)\"], South African Rock Lists, 2000 (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|[[Swiss Music Charts|Swiss Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"chchart\">[http://hitparade.ch/showitem.asp?interpret=George+Harrison&titel=What+Is+Life&cat=s \"George Harrison \u2013 What Is Life\"], hitparade.ch (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"Billboard_singles\">[http://www.allmusic.com/artist/george-harrison-mn0000209142/awards \"George Harrison > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 11 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]]<ref>{{cite book |title= Top Adult Contemporary: 1961-1993|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=1993 |publisher=Record Research |page=106}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|31\n|-\n|US ''[[Cash Box (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100<ref>[http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19710410.html Cash Box Top 100 4/10/71<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|US ''[[Record World]]'' Singles Chart<ref>Frank Mitchell (ed.), \"The Singles Chart\", ''[[Record World]]'', 27 March 1971, p. 31.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|West German [[Media Control Charts|Media Control Singles]]<ref name=\"Germany\">[http://www.officialcharts.de/song.asp?artist=George+Harrison&title=What+Is+Life&country=de \"Single \u2013 George Harrison, What Is Life\"], charts.de (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|}\n{{Col-2}}\n;Year-end charts\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Chart (1971)\n!Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian [[RPM Year-End|''RPM'' Singles Chart]]<ref>[http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.7590&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=mhe12pta2k83e08udtq66ot062 \"''RPM'' 100 Top Singles of '71\"], [[Library and Archives Canada]] (retrieved 3 June 2014).</ref>\n|41\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Dutch Singles Chart<ref>[http://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1971&cat=s \"Dutch charts jaaroverzichten 1971\" (''in Dutch'')], dutchcharts.nl (retrieved 3 June 2014).</ref>\n|45\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Cash Box''<ref>[http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1971YESP.html Cash Box YE Pop Singles - 1971<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626162215/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1971YESP.html |date=26 June 2015 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|48\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Olivia Newton-John version===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"clear: left;\"\n!Chart (1972)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Irish Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"Ireland\">[http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement \"''Search by Artist'' > Olivia Newton-John\"], irishcharts.ie (retrieved 14 June 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"ONJ UK\">[http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/olivia%20newton-john/ \"Artist: Olivia Newton-John\"], [[Official Charts Company]] (retrieved 4 June 2013).</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|16\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]]<ref>{{cite book|first= Joel |last= Whitburn |authorlink= Joel Whitburn |year= 1993 |title= Top Adult Contemporary: 1961\u20131993 |publisher= Record Research |page=175}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|34\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Dale C. Allison Jr., ''The Love There That's Sleeping: The Art and Spirituality of George Harrison'', Continuum (New York, NY, 2006; {{ISBN|978-0-8264-1917-0}}).\n* Keith Badman, ''The Beatles Diary Volume 2: After the Break-Up 1970\u20132001'', Omnibus Press (London, 2001; {{ISBN|0-7119-8307-0}}).\n* Harry Castleman & Walter J. Podrazik, ''All Together Now: The First Complete Beatles Discography 1961\u20131975'', Ballantine Books (New York, NY, 1976; {{ISBN|0-345-25680-8}}).\n* Alan Clayson, ''George Harrison'', Sanctuary (London, 2003; {{ISBN|1-86074-489-3}}).\n* The Editors of ''Rolling Stone'', ''Harrison'', Rolling Stone Press/Simon & Schuster (New York, NY, 2002; {{ISBN|0-7432-3581-9}}).\n* ''[[George Harrison: Living in the Material World]]'' DVD, [[Village Roadshow]], 2011 (directed by Martin Scorsese; produced by Olivia Harrison, Nigel Sinclair & Martin Scorsese).\n* Joshua M. Greene, ''Here Comes the Sun: The Spiritual and Musical Journey of George Harrison'', John Wiley & Sons (Hoboken, NJ, 2006; {{ISBN|978-0-470-12780-3}}).\n* John Harris, \"A Quiet Storm\", ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'', July 2001.\n* George Harrison, ''I Me Mine'', Chronicle Books (San Francisco, CA, 2002; {{ISBN|0-8118-3793-9}}).\n* Olivia Harrison, ''George Harrison: Living in the Material World'', Abrams (New York, NY, 2011; {{ISBN|978-1-4197-0220-4}}).\n* Elliot J. Huntley, ''Mystical One: George Harrison \u2013 After the Break-up of the Beatles'', Guernica Editions (Toronto, ON, 2006; {{ISBN|1-55071-197-0}}).\n* Ian Inglis, ''The Words and Music of George Harrison'', Praeger (Santa Barbara, CA, 2010; {{ISBN|978-0-313-37532-3}}).\n* Simon Leng, ''While My Guitar Gently Weeps: The Music of George Harrison'', Hal Leonard (Milwaukee, WI, 2006; {{ISBN|1-4234-0609-5}}).\n* Chip Madinger & Mark Easter, ''Eight Arms to Hold You: The Solo Beatles Compendium'', 44.1 Productions (Chesterfield, MO, 2000; {{ISBN|0-615-11724-4}}).\n* Tom Moon, ''1,000 Recordings to Hear Before You Die'', Workman Publishing (New York, NY, 2008; {{ISBN|978-0-7611-5385-6}}).\n* ''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll'', Fireside/Rolling Stone Press (New York, NY, 1995; {{ISBN|0-684-81044-1}}).\n* Robert Rodriguez, ''Fab Four FAQ 2.0: The Beatles' Solo Years, 1970\u20131980'', Backbeat Books (Milwaukee, WI, 2010; {{ISBN|978-1-4165-9093-4}}).\n* Nicholas Schaffner, ''The Beatles Forever'', McGraw-Hill (New York, NY, 1978; {{ISBN|0-07-055087-5}}).\n* [[Bruce Spizer]], ''The Beatles Solo on Apple Records'', 498 Productions (New Orleans, LA, 2005; {{ISBN|0-9662649-5-9}}).\n* Gary Tillery, ''Working Class Mystic: A Spiritual Biography of George Harrison'', Quest Books (Wheaton, IL, 2011; {{ISBN|978-0-8356-0900-5}}).\n* Bobby Whitlock with Marc Roberty, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=n9WQcf2fG-0C&pg=PA73&dq=%22All+Things+Must+Pass%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=RwJAUtTHBsiDlQWhzYD4Ag&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22All%20Things%20Must%20Pass%22&f=false Bobby Whitlock: A Rock 'n' Roll Autobiography]'', McFarland (Jefferson, NC, 2010; {{ISBN|978-0-7864-6190-5}}).\n* Bob Woffinden, ''The Beatles Apart'', Proteus (London, 1981; {{ISBN|0-906071-89-5}}).\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{youtube|fiH9edd25Bc|George Harrison - What Is Life (Official Music Video)}}\n{{George Harrison}}\n{{George Harrison singles}}\n\n[[Category:1970 songs]]\n[[Category:1971 singles]]\n[[Category:George Harrison songs]]\n[[Category:Olivia Newton-John songs]]\n[[Category:Apple Records singles]]\n[[Category:Pye Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by George Harrison]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by George Harrison]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Phil Spector]]\n[[Category:Music published by Harrisongs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings with Wall of Sound arrangements]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:British soul songs]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the George Harrison song|other uses|What Is Life (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = What Is Life\n| cover      = What Is Life (George Harrison single - cover art).jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| caption    = US picture sleeve\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[George Harrison]]\n| album      = [[All Things Must Pass]]\n| A-side     = \"[[My Sweet Lord]]\" <small>(UK)</small>\n| B-side     = \"[[Apple Scruffs (song)|Apple Scruffs]]\" <small>(except UK)</small>\n| released   = 15 February 1971 (US)\n| format     = [[gramophone record|7-inch vinyl]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Soul music|soul]]\n| length     = 4:22\n| label      = [[Apple Records|Apple]]\n| writer     = [[George Harrison]]\n| producer   = George Harrison, [[Phil Spector]]\n| prev_title = [[My Sweet Lord]]\n| prev_year  = 1970\n| next_title = [[Bangla Desh (song)|Bangla Desh]]\n| next_year  = 1971\n| misc       = {{Extra track listing\n | album  = [[All Things Must Pass]]\n | type   = single\n | tracks = {{All Things Must Pass tracks}}\n}}\n}}\n\"'''What Is Life'''\" is a song by the English musician [[George Harrison]], released on his 1970 triple album ''[[All Things Must Pass]]''. In many countries, it was issued as the second [[single (music)|single]] from the album, in February 1971, becoming a top-ten hit in the United States, Canada and elsewhere, and topping singles charts in Australia and Switzerland. In the United Kingdom, \"What Is Life\" appeared as the [[B-side]] to \"[[My Sweet Lord]]\", which was the best-selling single there of 1971. Harrison's backing musicians on the song include [[Eric Clapton]] and the entire [[Delaney & Bonnie|Delaney & Bonnie and Friends]] band, with whom he had toured during the final months of [[the Beatles]]. Harrison co-produced the recording with [[Phil Spector]], whose [[Wall of Sound]] production also employed a prominent string arrangement by [[John Barham]] and multiple acoustic rhythm guitars, played by Harrison's fellow [[Apple Records]] signings [[Badfinger]].\n\nAn uptempo composition in the [[Soul music|soul]] genre, \"What Is Life\" is one of several Harrison love songs that appear to be directed at both a woman and a deity. Harrison wrote the song in 1969 and originally intended it as a track for his friend and Apple prot\u00e9g\u00e9 [[Billy Preston]] to record. Built around a descending [[guitar riff]], it is one of Harrison's most popular compositions and was a regular inclusion in his live performances. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine has variously described it as a \"classic\"<ref name=\"RS 500 Albums\" /> and an \"exultant song of surrender\".<ref name=\"Eds of RS p 201\" />\n\n\"What Is Life\" has appeared in the soundtrack for feature films such as ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990), ''[[Patch Adams (film)|Patch Adams]]'' (1998), ''[[Big Daddy (1999 film)|Big Daddy]]'' (1999), ''[[Away We Go (film)|Away We Go]]'' (2009), ''[[This Is 40]]'' (2012) and ''[[Instant Family]]'' (2018). Harrison's original recording was included on the compilations ''[[The Best of George Harrison]]'' and ''[[Let It Roll: Songs by George Harrison|Let It Roll]]'', and live versions appear on his album ''[[Live in Japan (George Harrison album)|Live in Japan]]'' (1992) and in [[Martin Scorsese]]'s 2011 documentary ''[[George Harrison: Living in the Material World]]''. In 1972, [[Olivia Newton-John]] had a UK hit with her version of the song. [[Ronnie Aldrich]], [[the Ventures]] and [[Shawn Mullins]] are among the other artists who have covered the track.\n\n==Background and composition==\nEven before his temporary departure from [[the Beatles]] in January 1969 (documented in the song \"[[Wah-Wah (song)|Wah-Wah]]\"),<ref>Rodriguez, p. 379.</ref> their [[Apple Records]] label was an \"emancipating force\" for Harrison from the creative restrictions imposed on him within the band, according to his musical biographer, Simon Leng.<ref>Leng, pp. 55, 85.</ref> In his \"definitive\" article on ''[[All Things Must Pass]]'' for ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' magazine, [[John Harris (critic)|John Harris]] has written of Harrison's \"journey\" as a solo artist beginning in November 1968 \u2013 when he spent time in [[Woodstock, New York|Woodstock]] with [[Bob Dylan]] and [[the Band]] \u2013 and incorporating a series of other collaborations through the following eighteen months, including various Apple projects and a support role on [[Delaney & Bonnie]] and Friends' brief European tour.<ref>Harris, pp. 68\u201373.</ref> One of these projects, carried out intermittently from April to July 1969,<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, p. 80.</ref> was his production of ''[[That's the Way God Planned It]]'', an album by [[Billy Preston]], whom Harrison had met during the Beatles' [[The Beatles in Hamburg|Hamburg years]] and had recently recruited to guest on the band's troubled [[Let It Be (Beatles album)|''Get Back'']] sessions.<ref name=\"Irvin/Mojo p 82\">Jim Irvin, \"Close to the Edge\", ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'', December 2003, p. 82.</ref><ref>[http://applerecords.com/#!/albums/Album_EncouragingWords \"Encouraging Words\"], [[Apple Records]] (retrieved 16 February 2012).</ref> It was while driving up to a Preston session in London from his [[Kinfauns (Surrey)|home]] in [[Esher|Esher, Surrey]], that Harrison came up with the song \"What Is Life\".<ref name=\"Spizer p 222\">Spizer, p. 222.</ref>\n\nIn his autobiography, ''[[I, Me, Mine (book)|I, Me, Mine]]'', Harrison describes it as having been written \"very quickly\" and recalls that he thought it would be a perfect, \"catchy pop song\" for Preston to record.<ref name=\"IMM p 162\">George Harrison, p. 162.</ref> His lyrics, while simple, were similarly uplifting and universal:<ref name=\"Inglis p 26\">Inglis, p. 26.</ref><ref name=\"Unterberger/AM\" />\n\n{{quote|''What I feel, I can't say <br> But my love is there for you any time of day <br> But if it's not love that you need <br> Then I'll try my best to make everything succeed. <br> <br>Tell me, what is my life without your love? <br> And tell me, who am I without you, by my side?''}}\n\nThese lyrics have caused some debate among biographers and music critics, as to whether \"What Is Life\" should be viewed as a straightforward love song \u2013 perhaps a \"lovingly crafted paen\" to Harrison's wife [[Pattie Boyd|Pattie]], as [[Alan Clayson]] puts it<ref>Clayson, p. 298.</ref> \u2013 or a [[devotional song]] like many of Harrison's compositions.<ref name=\"Unterberger/AM\" /><ref>Allison, p. 158.</ref> Ian Inglis writes that the song title suggests a \"philosophical debate about the meaning of life\", yet its rendering as \"''what is my life''\" in the choruses \"reshapes [the meaning] completely\".<ref name=\"Inglis p 26\" /> Theologian [[Dale Allison]] finds no religious content in \"What Is Life\" but notes the \"failure of words to express feelings\" implied in the opening line (\"''What I feel, I can't say''\"), a recurring theme of Harrison's [[Spirituality|spiritual]] songs such as \"[[That Is All (song)|That Is All]]\", \"[[Mystical One]]\" and \"[[Pisces Fish]]\".<ref>Allison, pp. 124, 158.</ref> Joshua Greene, another religious academic, identifies the song as part of its parent album's \"intimately detailed account of a spiritual journey\": where \"[[Awaiting on You All]]\" shows Harrison \"convinced of his union with God\", \"What Is Life\" reveals him to be \"uncertain that he deserved such divine favor\".<ref>Greene, p. 181.</ref>\n\nThe song's second verse repeats what Inglis refers to as the \"somewhat confusing promise\" from Harrison (in lines 3 and 4) should his love be \"rejected\":<ref name=\"Inglis p 26\" />\n\n{{quote|''What I know, I can do <br> If I give my love out to everyone like you <br> But if it's not love that you need <br> Then I'll try my best to make everything succeed.''}}\n\nMusically, Simon Leng describes \"What Is Life\" as \"[[Motown]]-spiced\" and a comparatively rare example of its composer's willingness to embrace the role of \"entertainer\" in his songwriting.<ref>Leng, pp. 87\u201388.</ref>\n\nIn ''I Me Mine'', Harrison recalls that he changed his mind about offering \"What Is Life\" to Preston once he'd arrived at [[Olympic Studios]] and found the singer busy working on more typical material \u2013 or \"playing his funky stuff\" as Harrison puts it.<ref name=\"IMM p 162\" /><ref name=\"Spizer p 222\" /> Rather than attempt it with the Beatles during the band's concurrent ''[[Abbey Road]]'' sessions, he stockpiled the track with his many other unused songs from the period \u2013 \"[[All Things Must Pass (song)|All Things Must Pass]]\", \"[[Let It Down]]\", \"[[I'd Have You Anytime]]\" and \"[[Run of the Mill (George Harrison song)|Run of the Mill]]\" among them<ref>The Editors of ''Rolling Stone'', p. 187.</ref> \u2013 and revisited it a year later, after completing work on Preston's second Apple album, ''[[Encouraging Words]]''.<ref>Madinger & Easter, p. 426.</ref>\n\n==Recording==\nBy May 1970, having recently collaborated with \"genuine [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] heavy-weights\" such as [[Doris Troy]] and Preston, as well as participating in the \"[[blue-eyed soul]]\"<ref>Clayson, p. 274.</ref> Delaney & Bonnie European tour, along with [[Eric Clapton]], the previous December, Harrison was well placed to record \"What Is Life\", Leng observes.<ref name=\"Leng p 88\">Leng, p. 88.</ref> With [[Phil Spector]] as co-producer and all the Friends team on hand, the song was among the first tracks taped for Harrison's debut post-Beatles solo album;<ref name=\"Madinger & Easter p 429\" /> recording took place at [[Abbey Road Studios]] in London, during late May or early June.<ref name=\"Madinger & Easter p 429\" /><ref>Badman, p. 10.</ref> The same core of musicians \u2013 [[Bobby Whitlock]], [[Carl Radle]], [[Jim Gordon (musician)|Jim Gordon]], [[Bobby Keys]] and [[Jim Price (musician)|Jim Price]] \u2013 would similarly elevate other ''All Things Must Pass'' tracks such as \"Awaiting on You All\", \"[[Art of Dying (song)|Art of Dying]]\" and \"[[Hear Me Lord]]\".<ref>Leng, pp. 95\u201396, 97\u201398, 99.</ref>\n\nThe recording is defined by Harrison's descending, [[distortion (music)|fuzztone]] guitar [[riff]],<ref name=\"Eds of RS p 201\" /> which also serves as the [[motif (music)|motif]] for the chorus.<ref name=\"Unterberger/AM\">Richie Unterberger, [http://www.allmusic.com/song/what-is-life-t743156 \"George Harrison 'What Is Life'\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 22 February 2012).</ref> The track opens with this riff,<ref name=\"Gallucci/UCR\" /> which is then joined by Radle's bass and \"churning\" rhythm guitar from Clapton, before Gordon's drums bring the full band in.<ref name=\"Spizer p 222\" /><ref name=\"Leng p 87\" /> During the verses, Gordon moves to a square, Motown-style beat \u2013 or \"rock-steady [[Northern soul]] [[Beat (music)#Backbeat|backbeat]]\" in Leng's words<ref name=\"Leng p 88\" /> \u2013 before returning to the \"galloping rhythm\" of the more open, \"knockout\" choruses,<ref name=\"Eds of RS p 201\" /> and the song is driven equally by [[Badfinger]] drummer [[Mike Gibbins]]' powerful tambourine work.<ref name=\"Clayson p 296\" />\n\nOn \"What Is Life\", Spector provided what music critic [[David Fricke]] terms \"echo-drenched theater\", in the form of [[reverberation|reverb]]-heavy brass, soaring strings (arranged by [[John Barham]]) and \"a choir of multitracked Harrisons\".<ref name=\"Eds of RS p 201\">The Editors of ''Rolling Stone'', p. 201.</ref> The vocals and Barham's contribution, along with a brief [[Slide guitar|slide-guitar]] commentary from Harrison over the final verse,<ref name=\"Unterberger/AM\" /> were [[Overdubbing|overdubbed]] at [[Trident Studios]], most likely during late August through September.<ref>Madinger & Easter, pp. 427, 429.</ref> Dated 19 August, Spector's written comments on Harrison's early mix of the song had suggested a \"proper background voice\" was still needed;<ref name=\"Beatles Bible album\">[http://www.beatlesbible.com/people/george-harrison/albums/all-things-must-pass/ George Harrison: All Things Must Pass (album)], The Beatles Bible (retrieved 20 October 2012).</ref> like sound engineer [[Ken Scott]],<ref name=\"Beatles Bible\">[http://www.beatlesbible.com/people/george-harrison/songs/what-is-life/ George Harrison: What Is Life], The Beatles Bible (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref> Spector would be impressed with the result, saying, \"He was a great harmoniser&nbsp;... he could do all the [vocal] parts himself\" and rating Harrison \"one of the most commercial musicians and songwriters and quintessential players I've ever known in my entire career\".<ref>Olivia Harrison, p. 282.</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\"What Is Life\" was released in late November 1970 as the first track on side two of ''All Things Must Pass'', in its original, triple [[LP record|LP]] format.<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, p. 94.</ref><ref name=\"Spizer p 220\">Spizer, p. 220.</ref> Along with \"[[My Sweet Lord]]\" and \"[[Isn't It a Pity]]\", the song had already been identified as a potential hit single by Allan Steckler, manager of Apple's US operation.<ref name=\"Spizer p 220\" /> Backed by another album track, \"[[Apple Scruffs (song)|Apple Scruffs]]\", \"What Is Life\" was issued as a single in America on 15 February 1971 (as Apple 1828), just as the \"My Sweet Lord\"/\"Isn't It a Pity\" [[A-side and B-side#Double A-side|double A-side]] was finally slipping out of the top ten.<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, pp. 99, 352.</ref><ref>Badman, p. 26.</ref>\n\n[[File:Wil france.jpg|thumb|right|160px|French picture sleeve for the \"What Is Life\" single \u2013 a cropped and colorized version of [[Barry Feinstein]]'s cover image for ''[[All Things Must Pass]]'']]\nThe front of the single's US [[Record sleeve|picture sleeve]] consisted of a photo of Harrison playing guitar inside the central tower of his recently purchased home, [[Friar Park]], in [[Henley-on-Thames]].<ref>Spizer, pp. 226, 231.</ref> The tower's sole, octagonal-shaped room was an area that Harrison had adopted as his personal temple and [[meditation]] space.<ref>Tillery, p. 90.</ref> This picture was taken by photographer [[Barry Feinstein]], whose Camouflage Productions partner, [[Tom Wilkes]], originally used it as part of an elaborate poster intended as an insert in the album package. The poster featured a painting of the [[Hinduism|Hindu]] deity [[Krishna]] watching a group of naked maidens beside a bathing pond.<ref name=\"Spizer p 226\">Spizer, p. 226.</ref> Harrison apparently felt uncomfortable with the symbolism in Wilkes's design \u2013 the Friar Park tower image filled the top half of the poster, floating among clouds above the Krishna scene \u2013 so Wilkes abandoned the concept and instead used a darkened photo of Harrison inside the house as the album poster.<ref>Spizer, pp. 221, 226\u201328.</ref> The more common picture sleeve internationally was a close-up of Feinstein's ''All Things Must Pass'' front-cover image, taken on the main lawn of Friar Park.<ref>Harris, p. 73.</ref> In Denmark, the sleeve featured four shots of Harrison, again with guitar,<ref>Schaffner, p. 142.</ref> taken on stage during the Delaney & Bonnie tour.<ref>Peter Doggett, \"The Apple Years\", ''[[Record Collector]]'', April 2001, p. 36.</ref>\n\nAt the end of March, \"What Is Life\" peaked at number 10 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, p. 352.</ref> and number 7 on ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]''{{'}}s Top 100 chart,<ref name=\"Spizer p 231\">Spizer, p. 231.</ref> making Harrison the first ex-Beatle to have two top-ten hits in the United States.<ref>Rodriguez, p. 48.</ref><ref name=\"Mapes/Billboard\">Jillian Mapes, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/464932/george-harrisons-10-biggest-billboard-hits \"George Harrison's 10 Biggest Billboard Hits\"], [[Billboard (magazine)|billboard.com]], 29 November 2011 (retrieved 4 June 2014).</ref> The single was a success internationally, climbing to number 1 in Switzerland<ref name=\"chchart\" /> and on Australia's ''[[Go-Set]]'' National Top 60,<ref name=\"auschart\" /> and reaching the top three elsewhere in Europe and in Canada.<ref name=\"Tsosrt/GH singles\">[http://tsort.info/music/azncfw.htm \"George Harrison (Song artist 225)\"], Tsort pages (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref> In Britain, where Harrison had resisted issuing a single from ''All Things Must Pass'' until midway through January,<ref>Badman, pp. 22, 59.</ref> \"What Is Life\" appeared on the B-side to \"My Sweet Lord\"<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, p. 99.</ref> \u2013 a combination that became the [[List of best-selling singles by year in the United Kingdom|top-selling single]] of 1971 in that country.<ref>Dan Lane, [http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-biggest-selling-singles-of-every-year-revealed-1952-2011-1720/ \"The biggest selling singles of every year revealed! (1952\u20132011)\"], [[Official Charts Company]], 18 November 2012 (retrieved 3 June 2014).</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\"What Is Life\" is one of Harrison's most commercial and popular songs<ref>Allison, p. 132.</ref> \u2013 a \"spiritual guitar quest\" that \"became [a] classic\", according to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"RS 500 Albums\">[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/george-harrison-all-things-must-pass-19691231 \"500 Greatest Albums of All Time: George Harrison, 'All Things Must Pass'\"], [[Rolling Stone|rollingstone.com]] (retrieved 5 June 2014).</ref> On release, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine's reviewer wrote of \"What Is Life\" and \"Apple Scruffs\" as \"intriguing rhythm follows-ups\" to Harrison's previous single, which were \"sure to repeat that success\" and \"should prove big juke box items\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?hl=pt-BR&id=6QgEAAAAMBAJ&q=what+is+life#v=snippet&q=%22What%20is%20life%22&f=false \"Spotlight Singles\"], ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', 20 February 1971, p. 62 (retrieved 13 October 2013).</ref> In their ''Solo Beatles Compendium'', authors Chip Madinger and Mark Easter refer to it as an \"intensely catchy track\" and view its pairing with \"My Sweet Lord\" in the UK as perhaps the strongest of all of Harrison's singles.<ref name=\"Madinger & Easter p 429\">Madinger & Easter, p. 429.</ref> Writing in 1981, ''[[NME]]'' critic [[Bob Woffinden]] grouped \"What Is LIfe\" with \"My Sweet Lord\", \"Isn't It a Pity\" and \"Awaiting on You All\" as \"all excellent songs\".<ref>Woffinden, p. 38.</ref>\n\nReviewing the [[All Things Must Pass#2001|2001 reissue]] of ''All Things Must Pass'', for ''Rolling Stone'', James Hunter wrote of how the album's music \"exults in breezy rhythms\", among which \"the colorful revolutions of 'What Is Life' ... [move] like a [[Ferris wheel]]\".<ref>James Hunter, \"George Harrison ''All Things Must Pass'' 30th Anniversary reissue\", ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 29 March 2001; quoted in The Super Seventies \"Classic 500\", [http://www.superseventies.com/harrison1.html George Harrison \u2013 ''All Things Must Pass''] (retrieved 19 October 2012).</ref> The following year, in Rolling Stone Press's ''Harrison'' tribute book, David Fricke included \"What Is Life\" among his selection of \"essential Harrison performances\" (just three of which date from the ex-Beatle's solo years) and described the track as an \"exultant song of surrender\", abetted by Harrison's \"pumping [[Distortion (music)|fuzz guitar]]\" and the song's \"singalong magnetism\".<ref>The Editors of ''Rolling Stone'', pp. 196\u2013201.</ref> [[AllMusic]]'s [[Richie Unterberger]] similarly praises \"What Is Life\" for its \"anthemic\" qualities, \"particularly snazzy horn lines\", and a guitar riff that is \"one more entry in the catalog of George Harrison's book of arresting, low, descending guitar lines\".<ref name=\"Unterberger/AM\" />\n\nWriting in the book ''[[1,000 Recordings to Hear Before You Die]]'', author [[Tom Moon]] refers to \"the upbeat single 'What Is Life'\" as an example of how Harrison \"grabs what he needs from his old band \u2013 that insinuating [[Hook (music)|hook]] sense \u2013 and uses it to frame an utterly comfortable metaphysical discourse\".<ref name=\"Moon\">Moon, p. 345.</ref> Alan Clayson describes \"What Is Life\" as a seemingly \"lovey-dovey pop song\" that \"craftily renewed the simplistic tonic-to-dominant riff clich\u00e9\",<ref name=\"Clayson p 296\">Clayson, p. 296.</ref> while Simon Leng credits Harrison's \"innate ability to write very fine pop-rock songs\" and deems the result \"as innovative an exercise in rock-soul as The Temptations' '[[Cloud Nine (The Temptations song)|Cloud Nine]]'\".<ref name=\"Leng p 88\" /> Among Harrison biographers, only Ian Inglis is less than enthusiastic, acknowledging that Barham's orchestration and the other musicians give the track \"undoubted excitement and energy\", but lamenting that the song offers \"little overall coherence between words and music\".<ref name=\"Inglis p 26\" />\n\nIn a 2010 poll to find the \"10 Best George Harrison Songs\", [[AOL Radio]] listeners voted \"What Is Life\" third behind \"My Sweet Lord\" and \"[[Blow Away]]\".<ref>Boonsri Dickinson, [http://www.aolradioblog.com/2010/04/03/best-george-harrison-songs/ \"10 Best George Harrison Songs\"], [[AOL Radio]], April 2010 (retrieved 27 July 2012).</ref> A similar list by Michael Galluci of [[Ultimate Classic Rock]] placed it second (behind \"My Sweet Lord\"), as Galluci wrote of the track having \"a giant pop hook as its guide\" as well as \"the catchiest chorus Harrison ever penned\".<ref name=\"Gallucci/UCR\">Michael Gallucci, [http://ultimateclassicrock.com/george-harrison-songs/ \"Top 10 George Harrison Songs\"], [[Ultimate Classic Rock]] (retrieved 28 March 2014).</ref> In 2009, Matt Melis of [[Consequence of Sound]] listed it sixth among his \"Top Ten Songs by Ex-Beatles\", writing: \"it's arguable that Harrison's ''All Things Must Pass'' is the best solo album put out by a Beatle. 'What is Life' \u2026 with its riff-driven bounce, soaring harmonies on the choruses, and perfectly placed sax and trumpet, [is] probably Harrison's catchiest pop song.\"<ref>Matt Melis, [http://consequenceofsound.net/2009/04/list-em-carefully-top-ten-songs-by-ex-beatles/ \"List 'Em Carefully: Top Ten Songs by Ex-Beatles\"], [[Consequence of Sound]], 8 April 2009 (retrieved 28 March 2014).</ref> In the 2005 publication ''[[NME Originals]]: Beatles \u2013 The Solo Years 1970\u20131980'', Adrian Thrills rated it first among Harrison's \"ten solo gems\", adding: \"One of Harrison's greatest guitar riffs \u2013 brilliant pop.\"<ref>Chris Hunt (ed.), ''[[NME|NME Originals]]: Beatles \u2013 The Solo Years 1970\u20131980'', [[IPC Media \u2013 Inspire (Time Inc.)#Inspire|IPC Ignite!]] (London, 2005), p. 23.</ref> The song is said to be a favourite of [[Foo Fighters]] singer [[Dave Grohl]].<ref name=\"Eds of RS p 201\" /> In a ''Rolling Stone'' readers' poll, titled \"10 Greatest Solo Beatle Songs\", the song placed fourth, with the editor commenting: \"The track is deceptively simple, and more layers become apparent the more often you play it.\"<ref name=\"RS soloBeatles\">Andy Greene, [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/readers-poll-the-10-greatest-solo-beatle-songs-20130605/4-george-harrison-what-is-life-0593944 \"4. George Harrison \u2013 'What Is Life'\"], [[rollingstone.com]], 5 June 2013 (retrieved 30 May 2015).</ref> \"What Is Life\" has featured in Bruce Pollock's book ''The 7,500 Most Important Songs of 1944\u20132000'', Treble website's \"The Top 200 Songs of the 1970s\" (ranked at number 101) and [[Dave Thompson (author)|Dave Thompson]]'s ''1000 Songs That Rock Your World'' (at number 247).<ref>[http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/S6532.htm \"George Harrison 'What Is Life'\"], [[Acclaimed Music]] (retrieved 9 December 2014).</ref>\n\n==Subsequent releases and appearances in films==\n\"What Is Life\" was included on the 1976 compilation ''[[The Best of George Harrison]]'' as well as 2009's ''[[Let It Roll: Songs by George Harrison]]''.<ref>Inglis, pp. 65, 128.</ref> The song has also been featured in a number of popular movies: [[Martin Scorsese]]'s ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990), during the \"May 11, 1980\" sequence; [[Tom Shadyac]]'s ''[[Patch Adams (film)|Patch Adams]]'' (1998); [[Sam Mendes]]' ''[[Away We Go (film)|Away We Go]]'' (2009); and, more recently, ''[[Instant Family]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"imdb\">[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0365600/ \"George Harrison: Soundtrack\"], [[Internet Movie Database|IMDb]] (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref> In late 2012, \"What Is Life\" was used in advance promotion for the film ''[[This Is 40]]'', directed by [[Judd Apatow]],<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i9Vt9sP8OY8 \"''This Is 40'' Official Trailer #2 (2012)\"], YouTube, August 2012 (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref> although it was omitted from the accompanying soundtrack album.<ref>Stephen Thomas Erlewine, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-40-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0002441002 \"Various Artists ''This Is 40 (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 3 June 2014).</ref> According to ''Rolling Stone'': \"Today, many people know it merely as a song from all those soundtracks: it's in ''This Is 40'', ''Patch Adams'', ''Goodfellas'' and many more. It's almost as ubiquitous as '[[Let My Love Open the Door]]' or '[[Solsbury Hill (song)|Solsbury Hill]].'\"<ref name=\"RS soloBeatles\" /> In Scorsese's 2011 documentary ''[[George Harrison: Living in the Material World]]'', \"What Is Life\" plays over a sequence of 1969 photos of Harrison \u2013 with, variously, Preston, [[Jackie Lomax]], the [[Plastic Ono Band]], Clapton and [[Ravi Shankar]] \u2013 immediately before which, archive footage shows him discussing the restrictions he felt within the Beatles and how the band \"had to implode\".<ref>''George Harrison: Living in the Material World'', Disc 2; event occurs between 13:48 and 14:50.</ref>\n\nAn alternative studio version of \"What Is Life\" \u2013 in fact, a rough mix of the original backing track with different orchestration (in this case, [[piccolo trumpet]] and [[oboe]])<ref>Leng, p. 284.</ref> \u2013 was issued as one of five bonus tracks on the 2001 remaster of ''All Things Must Pass''.<ref>Huntley, p. 307.</ref> In the accompanying booklet, Harrison writes that this orchestral arrangement was discarded because he \"didn't like the feel\".<ref>George Harrison's liner notes, booklet accompanying ''All Things Must Pass'' reissue ([[Gnome Records]], 2001; produced by George Harrison & Phil Spector), p. 11.</ref> Speaking to ''Billboard'' editor-in-chief [[Timothy White (editor)|Timothy White]] in December 2000, Harrison explained the reason for the lack of a guide vocal on this version: \"I'm playing the fuzz guitar part that goes all through the song. So all I could do on the [initial] take was to give the band the cue line \u2013 the first line of each verse \u2013 and then go back to playing that riff. So that rough mix without the vocal \u2013 I'd forgot all about it \u2026\"<ref>Timothy White, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/80788/george-harrison-all-things-in-good-time \"George Harrison: 'All Things' In Good Time\"], [[Billboard (magazine)|billboard.com]], 8 January 2001 (retrieved 3 June 2014).</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, this instrumental version also appeared as a bonus track on the 2014 ''[[The Apple Years 1968\u201375|Apple Years 1968\u201375]]'' reissue of ''All Things Must Pass''.<ref name=\"Marchese/SecondDisc\">Joe Marchese, [http://theseconddisc.com/2014/09/02/give-me-love-george-harrisons-apple-years-are-collected-on-new-box-set/ \"Give Me Love: George Harrison\u2019s 'Apple Years' Are Collected On New Box Set\"], The Second Disc, 2 September 2014 (retrieved 26 September 2014).</ref>\n\n===Music video===\nCoinciding with the release of ''The Apple Years 1968\u201375'', Harrison's widow and son, [[Olivia Harrison|Olivia]] and [[Dhani Harrison]], held an online competition in which filmmakers were invited to create a video clip for \"What Is Life\". The winner would receive a $5000 cash prize and their entry would became the official video for the track, appearing on the Harrison [[YouTube]] channel and other media platforms.<ref>Steve Marinucci, [https://www.axs.com/olivia-dhani-harrison-to-choose-winner-of-what-is-life-music-video-con-19893 \"Olivia & Dhani Harrison to choose winner of 'What Is Life' music video contest\"], [[AXS (company)|axs.com]], 15 September 2014 (retrieved 21 May 2017).</ref> In November, Olivia and Dhani selected Brandon Moore of [[Oakland, CA]], as the winner, for his video featuring dance performances by Emma Rubinowitz and Esteban Hernandez of the [[San Francisco Ballet]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Genero.tv \u2018What is Life\u2019 Winner Announced |url=http://www.georgeharrison.com/genero-tv-what-is-life-winner-announced/ |website=georgeharrison.com |accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dancers in Yellow Frolic Around the Woods in the Official Video for the George Harrison\u2019s \u2018What Is Life\u2019 |url=https://laughingsquid.com/george-harrison-what-is-life/ |website=Laughing Squid |accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=George Harrison - What Is Life (Official Music Video) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fiH9edd25Bc |website=YouTube |publisher=George Harrison |accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Live performance==\nA live version of the song, recorded with Eric Clapton and his band in December 1991, is available on Harrison's 1992 album ''[[Live in Japan (George Harrison album)|Live in Japan]]'' album.<ref>Stephen Thomas Erlewine, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/live-in-japan-mw0000334804 \"George Harrison ''Live in Japan''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 20 October 2012).</ref> The performance was recorded at [[Tokyo Dome]] on 17 December,<ref>Madinger & Easter, pp. 483, 484.</ref> during the final show of the tour.<ref>Badman, pp. 471, 473.</ref>\n\nPart of a concert performance of \"What Is Life\" from Harrison's 1974 North American tour with Shankar is included in Scorsese's ''George Harrison: Living in the Material World''.<ref>''George Harrison: Living in the Material World'' Disc 2; event occurs between 50.51 and 51.49.</ref> While challenging the commonly held view that this controversial 1974 tour was a \"disaster\",<ref>Jim Miller, \"George Harrison: ''Dark Horse'' (LP Review)\", ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 13 February 1975, p. 180.</ref><ref>Rodriguez, p. 59.</ref> Simon Leng writes of a [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]] performance of \"What Is Life\" that was \"greeted with a reception that matched anything the New York audience at the [[The Concert for Bangladesh|Bangla Desh concerts]] expressed\".<ref>Leng, p. 172.</ref>\n\n==Cover versions==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = What Is Life\n| cover      = Picture sleeve for Olivia Newton-John single What Is Life.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Picture sleeve for the West German release (on [[Polydor Records]])\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Olivia Newton-John]]\n| album      = [[Olivia (Olivia Newton-John album)|Olivia]]\n| B-side     = I'm a Small and Lonely Light\n| released   = 1972\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]], [[Pop music|pop]]\n| length     = 3:21\n| label      = [[Pye International Records|Pye International]]\n| writer     = [[George Harrison]]\n| producer   = [[Bruce Welch]], [[John Farrar]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n===Olivia Newton-John===\nEnglish born Australian pop singer [[Olivia Newton-John]] recorded \"What Is Life\", along with a version of Harrison's ''All Things Must Pass'' track \"[[Behind That Locked Door]]\",<ref>[http://www.wer-singt.de/song_Behind+That+Locked+Door.htm \"Behind That Locked Door\"], wer-singt.de (retrieved 9 October 2012).</ref> for her 1972 album ''[[Olivia (Olivia Newton-John album)|Olivia]]''.<ref>[http://www.onlyolivia.com/music/albums/olivia.html \"Albums: ''Olivia''\"], onlyolivia.com (retrieved 9 October 2012).</ref> The song was arranged and produced by [[Bruce Welch]] of [[the Shadows]] and [[John Farrar]],<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=5710466 Label credit], \"What Is Life / I'm a Small and Lonely Light\" single, Interfusion Records, 1972.</ref> who was Newton-John's regular producer and collaborator during the 1970s.<ref>''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll'', pp. 709, 887.</ref>\n\nReleased as a single in some countries, this version reached the UK top 20 in March 1972,<ref name=\"Clayson p 296\" /><ref>Huntley, p. 56.</ref> peaking at number 16.<ref name=\"ONJ UK\" />{{refn|group=nb|Her previous single, a US hit in late 1971, was a cover of the Dylan song \"[[If Not For You]]\",<ref>''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll'', p. 709.</ref> based on the Harrison arrangement from ''All Things Must Pass'' rather than Dylan's own reading.<ref name=\"Clayson p 296\" /><ref>Joe Viglione, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/if-not-for-you-mw0000739358 \"Olivia Newton-John ''If Not for You''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 4 June 2014).</ref>}} It has since appeared on Newton-John compilation albums such as ''[[Back to Basics: The Essential Collection 1971\u20131992]]'' (1992)<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Olivia-Back-To-Basics-The-Essential-Collection-1971-1992/release/2974614 \"Olivia* \u2013 Back to Basics: The Essential Collection 1971\u20131992\"], [[Discogs]] (retrieved 14 June 2014).</ref> and ''[[The Definitive Collection (Olivia Newton-John album)|The Definitive Collection]]'' (2002).<ref>Heather Phares, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/definitive-collection-mw0000739711 \"Olivia Newton-John ''Definitive Collection''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 13 June 2014).</ref>\n\n===Other artists===\nIn 1971, British [[easy listening]] pianist [[Ronnie Aldrich]] covered \"What Is Life\" (as well as \"My Sweet Lord\") on his album ''Love Story''.<ref>Al Campbell, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/love-story-the-way-we-were-mw0000575419 \"Ronnie Aldridge ''Love Story / The Way We Were''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 16 September 2012).</ref> That same year, a version by [[the Ventures]] appeared on their ''New Testament'' album.<ref>Bruce Eder, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/new-testament-mw0000868440 \"The Ventures ''New Testament''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 4 August 2012).</ref> Also in 1971, a Finnish-language version of the song, titled \"Mik\u00e4 Saa Ihmisen El\u00e4m\u00e4\u00e4n\", was released as a single by local singer Oliver \u2013 better known as Veikko Laiho, of [[the Laiho Trio]].<ref>[http://finnpicks.blogspot.com.au/2011_03_01_archive.html \"What Is Life \u2013 Mik\u00e4 Saa Ihmisen El\u00e4m\u00e4\u00e4n\"], Finnpicks, 3 March 2011 (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref>\n\nIn 1992, [[Nicola Sirkis]] covered the song on the album ''Dans La Lune&nbsp;...''<ref name=\"GH covers\">[http://www.coversproject.com/artist/george%20harrison/ \"George Harrison Cover Songs\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221105921/https://www.coversproject.com/artist/george%20harrison |date=21 February 2017 }}, The Covers Project (retrieved 4 August 2012).</ref> A version by [[Shawn Mullins]] was released as a single in 1999<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Shawn-Mullins-What-Is-Life/release/3624755 \"Shawn Mullins \u2013 What Is Life\"], [[Discogs]] (retrieved 14 June 2014).</ref> and plays over the closing credits of the [[Adam Sandler]] movie ''[[Big Daddy (1999 film)|Big Daddy]]'' (1999).<ref name=\"imdb\" /><ref>Stephen Thomas Erlewine, [http://www.allmusic.com/album/big-daddy-mw0000241564 \"Original Soundtrack ''Big Daddy''\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref>\n\nFollowing Harrison's death, Japanese band the Collectors contributed a recording of \"What Is Life\" to the ''Gentle Guitar Dreams'' tribute album, released in May 2002.<ref>[http://www.cdjapan.co.jp/detailview.html?KEY=AMCM-10021 \"Various Artists ''Gentle Guitar Dreams''\"], CD Japan (retrieved 15 September 2012).</ref> Classical guitarist Joseph Breznikar recorded a version of the song for his 2003 tribute album ''George Harrison Remembered: A Touch of Class''.<ref name=\"Breznikar\">[http://www.secondhandsongs.com/release/50957 \"''George Harrison Remembered: A Touch of Class'' \u2013 Joseph Breznikar\"], Second Hand Songs (retrieved 19 September 2012).</ref> In November 2004, [[Neal Morse]] released his recording of \"What Is Life\" on the special-edition version of his album ''[[One (Neal Morse album)|One]]''.<ref name=\"SecondHand various\">[http://www.secondhandsongs.com/work/72046 \"'What Is Life' \u2013 George Harrison\"], Second Hand Songs (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref> [[Les Fradkin]] included a cover of \"What Is Life\" on his 2005 tribute CD ''Something for George''.<ref>[http://www.lesfradkin.com/products-group-39.html \"George Harrison/Beatles Vocal Tribute CDs\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610001814/http://www.lesfradkin.com/products-group-39.html |date=10 June 2013 }}, lesfradkin.com (retrieved 16 October 2012).</ref>\n\n\"What Is Life\" was performed live at George Fest 2014 by [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]]. The recording is available on YouTube.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wXMq3QJwJiA \"Weird Al Covers George Harrison's \"What is Life\" at George Fest 2014\"]</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nThe following musicians are believed to have played on \"What Is Life\":<ref name=\"Spizer p 222\"/><ref name=\"Leng p 87\">Leng, p. 87.</ref>\n\n* [[George Harrison]] \u2013 vocals, lead guitar, acoustic guitar, [[slide guitar]], backing vocals\n* [[Eric Clapton]] \u2013 rhythm guitar\n* [[Bobby Whitlock]] \u2013 organ<ref>Whitlock, p. 80.</ref>\n* [[Carl Radle]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Jim Gordon (musician)|Jim Gordon]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Jim Price (musician)|Jim Price]] \u2013 trumpet, horn arrangement\n* [[Bobby Keys]] \u2013 saxophone\n* [[Pete Ham]] \u2013 acoustic guitar\n* [[Tom Evans (musician)|Tom Evans]] \u2013 acoustic guitar\n* [[Joey Molland]] \u2013 acoustic guitar\n* [[Mike Gibbins]] \u2013 tambourine\n* [[John Barham]] \u2013 string arrangement\n\n==Chart performance==\n\n===George Harrison version===\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n;Weekly charts\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1971)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australian ''[[Go-Set]]'' National Top 60<ref name=\"auschart\">[http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1971/19710508.html \"Go-Set Australian charts \u2013 8 May 1971\"], poparchives.com.au (retrieved 13 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|[[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|Austrian Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"atchart\">[http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=George+Harrison&titel=What+Is+Life&cat=s \"George Harrison \u2013 What Is Life\"], austriancharts.at (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|Belgian [[Ultratop|Ultratop Singles]]<ref name=\"Belgian singles\">[http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=George+Harrison&titel=What+Is+Life&cat=s \"George Harrison \u2013 What Is Life\"], ultratop.be (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|Canadian [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'' 100 Singles]]<ref>[http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.5229&type=2&interval=24&PHPSESSID=tflvluuu3gmgse7n7epkm834m4 \"''RPM'' 100 Singles, 17 April 1971\"], [[Library and Archives Canada]] (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|Dutch [[MegaCharts|MegaChart Singles]]<ref name=\"nlchart\">[http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=George+Harrison&titel=What+Is+Life&cat=s \"George Harrison \u2013 What Is Life\"], dutchcharts.nl (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|Japanese [[Oricon]] Singles Chart<ref name=\"jpchart\">[http://homepage1.nifty.com/tuty/after_beatles_george_singlechartaction_japan.htm \"George Harrison: Chart Action (Japan)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303201239/http://homepage1.nifty.com/tuty/after_beatles_george_singlechartaction_japan.htm |date=3 March 2016 }}, homepage1.nifty.com (retrieved 11 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|19\n|-\n|New Zealand ''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'' Chart<ref name=\"NZchart\">[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20listener&qsongid=3899#n_view_location Search: \"What Is Life\"], Flavour of New Zealand/Steve Kohler, 2007 (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|Norwegian [[VG-lista|VG-lista Singles]]<ref name=\"nochart\">[http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=George+Harrison&titel=What+Is+Life&cat=s \"George Harrison \u2013 What Is Life\"], norwegiancharts.com (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|South African Springbok Singles Chart<ref>[http://www.rock.co.za/files/sa_charts_1969_1989_songs_(W-Z).html \"SA Charts 1969\u20131989 Songs (W\u2013Z)\"], South African Rock Lists, 2000 (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|[[Swiss Music Charts|Swiss Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"chchart\">[http://hitparade.ch/showitem.asp?interpret=George+Harrison&titel=What+Is+Life&cat=s \"George Harrison \u2013 What Is Life\"], hitparade.ch (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"Billboard_singles\">[http://www.allmusic.com/artist/george-harrison-mn0000209142/awards \"George Harrison > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles\"], [[AllMusic]] (retrieved 11 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]]<ref>{{cite book |title= Top Adult Contemporary: 1961-1993|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=1993 |publisher=Record Research |page=106}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|31\n|-\n|US ''[[Cash Box (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100<ref>[http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19710410.html Cash Box Top 100 4/10/71<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|US ''[[Record World]]'' Singles Chart<ref>Frank Mitchell (ed.), \"The Singles Chart\", ''[[Record World]]'', 27 March 1971, p. 31.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|West German [[Media Control Charts|Media Control Singles]]<ref name=\"Germany\">[http://www.officialcharts.de/song.asp?artist=George+Harrison&title=What+Is+Life&country=de \"Single \u2013 George Harrison, What Is Life\"], charts.de (retrieved 14 April 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|}\n{{Col-2}}\n;Year-end charts\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Chart (1971)\n!Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian [[RPM Year-End|''RPM'' Singles Chart]]<ref>[http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.7590&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=mhe12pta2k83e08udtq66ot062 \"''RPM'' 100 Top Singles of '71\"], [[Library and Archives Canada]] (retrieved 3 June 2014).</ref>\n|41\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Dutch Singles Chart<ref>[http://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1971&cat=s \"Dutch charts jaaroverzichten 1971\" (''in Dutch'')], dutchcharts.nl (retrieved 3 June 2014).</ref>\n|45\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Cash Box''<ref>[http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1971YESP.html Cash Box YE Pop Singles - 1971<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626162215/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1971YESP.html |date=26 June 2015 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|48\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Olivia Newton-John version===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"clear: left;\"\n!Chart (1972)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Irish Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"Ireland\">[http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement \"''Search by Artist'' > Olivia Newton-John\"], irishcharts.ie (retrieved 14 June 2014).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"ONJ UK\">[http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/olivia%20newton-john/ \"Artist: Olivia Newton-John\"], [[Official Charts Company]] (retrieved 4 June 2013).</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|16\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]]<ref>{{cite book|first= Joel |last= Whitburn |authorlink= Joel Whitburn |year= 1993 |title= Top Adult Contemporary: 1961\u20131993 |publisher= Record Research |page=175}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|34\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Dale C. Allison Jr., ''The Love There That's Sleeping: The Art and Spirituality of George Harrison'', Continuum (New York, NY, 2006; {{ISBN|978-0-8264-1917-0}}).\n* Keith Badman, ''The Beatles Diary Volume 2: After the Break-Up 1970\u20132001'', Omnibus Press (London, 2001; {{ISBN|0-7119-8307-0}}).\n* Harry Castleman & Walter J. Podrazik, ''All Together Now: The First Complete Beatles Discography 1961\u20131975'', Ballantine Books (New York, NY, 1976; {{ISBN|0-345-25680-8}}).\n* Alan Clayson, ''George Harrison'', Sanctuary (London, 2003; {{ISBN|1-86074-489-3}}).\n* The Editors of ''Rolling Stone'', ''Harrison'', Rolling Stone Press/Simon & Schuster (New York, NY, 2002; {{ISBN|0-7432-3581-9}}).\n* ''[[George Harrison: Living in the Material World]]'' DVD, [[Village Roadshow]], 2011 (directed by Martin Scorsese; produced by Olivia Harrison, Nigel Sinclair & Martin Scorsese).\n* Joshua M. Greene, ''Here Comes the Sun: The Spiritual and Musical Journey of George Harrison'', John Wiley & Sons (Hoboken, NJ, 2006; {{ISBN|978-0-470-12780-3}}).\n* John Harris, \"A Quiet Storm\", ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'', July 2001.\n* George Harrison, ''I Me Mine'', Chronicle Books (San Francisco, CA, 2002; {{ISBN|0-8118-3793-9}}).\n* Olivia Harrison, ''George Harrison: Living in the Material World'', Abrams (New York, NY, 2011; {{ISBN|978-1-4197-0220-4}}).\n* Elliot J. Huntley, ''Mystical One: George Harrison \u2013 After the Break-up of the Beatles'', Guernica Editions (Toronto, ON, 2006; {{ISBN|1-55071-197-0}}).\n* Ian Inglis, ''The Words and Music of George Harrison'', Praeger (Santa Barbara, CA, 2010; {{ISBN|978-0-313-37532-3}}).\n* Simon Leng, ''While My Guitar Gently Weeps: The Music of George Harrison'', Hal Leonard (Milwaukee, WI, 2006; {{ISBN|1-4234-0609-5}}).\n* Chip Madinger & Mark Easter, ''Eight Arms to Hold You: The Solo Beatles Compendium'', 44.1 Productions (Chesterfield, MO, 2000; {{ISBN|0-615-11724-4}}).\n* Tom Moon, ''1,000 Recordings to Hear Before You Die'', Workman Publishing (New York, NY, 2008; {